cement=6&pgtype=sectionfront online review]\n* Pomfret, John. ''The Beautiful Country and the Middle Kingdom: America and China, 1776 to the Present'' (2016) [https://www.nytimes.com/2016/12/30/books/review/beautiful-country-middle-kingdom-john-pomfret.html?rref=collection%2Fsectioncollection%2Fbooks&action=click&contentCollection=books&region=stream&module=stream_unit&version=latest&contentPlacement=6&pgtype=sectionfront review]\n* Riccards, Michael P. ''The Presidency and the Middle Kingdom'' (2000)\n* Rose, Robert S. et al. ''Re-examining the Cold War: U.S.-China Diplomacy, 1954\u20131973'' (2002)\n* Schaller, Michael. ''The United States and China: Into the Twenty-First Century'' 4th ed 2015) \n* Song, Yuwu, ed. ''Encyclopedia of Chinese-American Relations'' (McFarland, 2006)\n* Spence, Jonathan D. ''To Change China'' (1980)\n* Spence, Jonathan. \"Western Perceptions of China from the Late Sixteenth Century to the Present\" in Paul S. Ropp, ed.''Heritage of China: Contemporary Perspectives on Chinese Civilization'' (1990) [https://books.google.com/books?id=zm6Sm64y5CwC&pg=PA10 excerpts]\n* Sutter, Robert G.  ''U.S.-Chinese Relations: Perilous Past, Pragmatic Present'' (2010).\n* Sutter, Robert G. ''Historical Dictionary of United States-China Relations'' (2005).\n* Tuchman, Barbara. ''Stilwell and the American Experience in China, 1911\u20131945'' (1971)\n* Varg, Paul A. \"Sino\u2010American Relations Past and Present.\" ''Diplomatic History'' 4.2 (1980): 101\u2013112. [https://www.jstor.org/stable/24911230 online]\n* Wang, Dong. ''The United States and China: A History from the Eighteenth Century to the Present'' (2013)\n\n===Recent===\n*Blanchard, Jean-Marc F.,  and Simon Shen, eds. ''Conflict and Cooperation in Sino-US Relations: Change and Continuity, Causes and Cures'' (Routledge, 2015)\n*Davis, Samuel R. ''Out flying the eagle: China's drive for domestic economic innovation and its impact on US-China relations'' (MA thesis, Naval Postgraduate School, 2014) [http://calhoun.nps.edu/public/bitstream/handle/10945/41366/14Mar_Davis_Samuel.pdf?sequence=1 Pdf.]\n* Fenby, Jonathan and Trey McArver. ''The Eagle and the Dragon: Donald Trump, Xi Jinping and the Fate of US/China Relations'' (2019)\n* Foot, Rosemary. ''The practice of power: US relations with China since 1949'' (Oxford University Press, 1995).\n*{{Cite book |first1=Rosemary |last1=Foot |first2=Andrew |last2=Walter |title=China, the United States, and Global Order |publisher=Cambridge University Press |year=2012 |isbn=9780521725194}}\n* Fravel, M. Taylor. ''Active Defense: China\u2019s Military Strategy since 1949'' (Princeton University Press, 2019) [https://issforum.org/to/ir11-12 online reviews]\n*{{Cite book |first=Aaron L. |last=Friedberg |authorlink=Aaron Friedberg |title=A Contest for Supremacy: China, America, and the Struggle for Mastery in Asia |publisher=W.W. Norton |year=2011 |isbn=9780393068283}}\n* Garver, John W. ''China's Quest: The History of the Foreign Relations of the People's Republic'' (2015), 59-91, 232-58, 286-314, 557-578. 607-673.  \n*{{Cite journal | last = Goldstein | first = Avery | title = First things first: the pressing danger of crisis instability in US-China relations | journal = [[International Security (journal)|International Security]] | volume = 37 | issue = 4 | pages = 49\u201389 | doi = 10.1162/ISEC_a_00114 | date = Spring 2013 | ref = harv }} [http://myweb.rollins.edu/tlairson/china/uschinacrisis.pdf Pdf.]\n* Madan, Tanvi. \"With an eye to the east: the China factor and the US-India relationship, 1949-1979\" (PhD dissertation, U Texas 2012).  [https://repositories.lib.utexas.edu/bitstream/handle/2152/25110/madan_dissertation_20122.pdf?sequence=1 online free]\n* [[Kishore Mahbubani|Mahbubani, Kishore]], \"What China Threat?  How the United States and China can avoid war\", ''[[Harper's Magazine]]'', vol. 338, no. 2025 (February 2019), pp.&nbsp;39\u201344.  \"China could... remain a different [[polity]]\u2014... not a [[liberal democracy]]\u2014and still not be a threatening one.\" (p.&nbsp;44.)\n*Mann, Jim. ''About face: A history of America's curious relationship with China, from Nixon to Clinton'' (Knopf, 1999)\n*Men, Jing, and Wei Shen, eds. ''The EU, the US and China - Towards a New International Order?'' (2014) {{ISBN|1781003467}}\n*Roach, Stephen S. ''Unbalanced: the codependency of America and China'' (Yale UP, 2015).\n* Ropp, Paul S. ed.''Heritage of China: Contemporary Perspectives on Chinese Civilization'' (1990) [https://books.google.com/books?id=zm6Sm64y5CwC&pg=PA10 excerpts]\n*Roberts, Priscilla. \"New Perspectives on Cold War History from China,\" ''Diplomatic History'' 41:2 (April 2017) [https://networks.h-net.org/system/files/contributed-files/ar722.pdf online]\n*{{Cite book |editor-first=David |editor-last=Shambaugh |title=Tangled Titans: The United States and China |publisher=Rowman & Littlefield |year=2012 |isbn=978-1442219700}}\n*Schoen, Douglas E.  and Melik Kaylan. ''Return to Winter: Russia, China, and the New Cold War Against America'' (2015)\n*Steinberg, James, and Michael E. O'Hanlon, eds. ''Strategic Reassurance and Resolve: US-China Relations in the Twenty-First Century'' (Princeton UP, 2014)\n*Wang, Dong. \"Grand Strategy, Power Politics, and China\u2019s Policy toward the United States in the 1960s,\" ''Diplomatic History'' 42:1 (April 2017): 265\u2013287; \n*[[Odd Arne Westad|Westad, Odd Arne]], \"The Sources of Chinese Conduct: Are Washington and Beijing Fighting a New Cold War?\", ''[[Foreign Affairs]]'', vol. 98, no. 5 (September / October 2019), pp.&nbsp;86\u201395. \"If some unifying factor does not intervene, the decline in the United States' ability to act purposefully will, sooner than most people imagine, mean not just a [[multipolar world]] but an unruly world \u2013 one in which fear, hatred, and ambition hold everyone hostage to the basest instincts of the human imagination.\" (p.&nbsp;95.) \n*Wheeler, Norton. ''Role of American NGOs in China's Modernization: Invited Influence'' (Routledge, 2014) 240 pp. [http://www.h-net.org/reviews/showpdf.php?id=43437 online review]\n*Xia, Yafeng and Zhi Liang. \"China\u2019s Diplomacy toward the United States in the Twentieth Century: A Survey of the Literature,\" ''Diplomatic History'' 42:1 (April 2017): 241\u2013264.\n*{{Cite journal | last = Yan | first = Xuetong | title = The instability of China\u2013US relations | journal = [[The Chinese Journal of International Politics]] | volume = 3 | issue = 3 | pages = 263\u201392 | doi = 10.1093/cjip/poq009 | date = Autumn 2010 | ref = harv | url = https://semanticscholar.org/paper/beb70a602f468388ce394788ae4f3a2b697f275d }}\n* Yim, Kwan Ha. ''China and the US: 1955-63'' (1973). [https://archive.org/details/chinaus19556300yimk online]\n* Yim, Kwan Ha. ''China 1964-72'' (1975). [https://archive.org/details/chinaus1964720000yimk online]\n* Yim, Kwan Ha. ''China since Mao'' (1980) pp 129-60 [https://archive.org/details/chinasincemao0000yimk/page/n9 online]\n*Zhang, Biwu. ''Chinese Perceptions of the U.S.: An Exploration of China's Foreign Policy Motivations'' (Lexington Books; 2012) 266 pages; Chinese views of America's power, politics, and economics, as well as the country as a source of threat or opportunity.\n*{{Cite journal | last = Zhao | first = Quansheng | title = America's response to the rise of China and Sino\u2010US relations | journal = Asian Journal of Political Science | volume = 13 | issue = 2 | pages = 1\u201327 | doi = 10.1080/02185370508434256 | date = December 2005 | ref = harv }}\n\n===Primary sources===\n*{{citation|author=Jeffrey A. Engel, ed.|title=The China Diary of George H. W. Bush: The Making of a Global President|chapter-url=https://books.google.com/books?id=jRvdwoKQOgQC&pg=PA356|year=2011|publisher=Princeton UP|isbn=978-1400829613|jstor=j.ctt7stg8|chapter=The Making of a Global President}}\n\n===China White Paper 1949===\n*Lyman Van Slyke, ed. ''The China White Paper: August 1949'' (1967: 2 vol. Stanford U.P.); 1124 pp.; copy of official U.S. Department of State. ''China White Paper: 1949'' [https://books.google.com/books?id=HuB6gPHeP_cC&printsec=copyright#v=onepage&q&f=false vol 1 online at Google]; [https://archive.org/details/VanSlykeLymanTheChinaWhitePaper1949 online vol 1 pdf]; vol 1 consists of history; vol 2 consists of primary sources and is not online; see [http://www.worldcat.org/title/china-white-paper-august-1949-united-states-relations-with-china-with-special-reference-to-the-period-1944-1949/oclc/63130113 library holdings via World Cat]\n**excerpts appear in Barton Bernstein and Allen J. Matusow, eds. ''The Truman Administration: A Documentary History'' (1966) pp.&nbsp;299\u2013355\n\n{{China\u2013United States relations}}\n{{China\u2013United States proxy conflict}}\n{{Foreign relations of China}}\n{{Foreign relations of the United States |expanded=Bilateral}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Sino-American Relations}}\n[[Category:China\u2013United States relations| ]]\n[[Category:Bilateral relations of the United States|China]]\n[[Category:Bilateral relations of China|United States]]\n", "text_old": "{{About|relations between the [[United States]] and [[China]], whose [[China and the United Nations|United Nations seat]] is occupied by the [[History of the People's Republic of China|People's Republic of China]]|relations between the [[Taiwan|Republic of China]] and the [[United States]]|Taiwan\u2013United States relations}}\n{{Short description|1=Diplomatic relations between the People's Republic of China and the United States of America}}\n{{Use American English|date=February 2019}}\n{{Infobox bilateral relations|China\u2013United States|China|USA|map=China USA Locator.svg|envoytitle1 =[[List of ambassadors of China to the United States|Ambassador]] |envoy1 =[[Cui Tiankai]] |envoytitle2 =[[List of ambassadors of the United States to China|Ambassador]]|envoy2 =[[Terry Branstad]] |mission1 = [[Embassy of China in Washington, D.C.|Chinese Embassy, Washington, D.C.]] |mission2 = [[Embassy of the United States, Beijing|United States Embassy, Beijing]]}}\n[[File:President Trump at the G20 (48162296516).jpg|thumb|upright=1.2|Chinese Chairman [[Xi Jinping]] with U.S. President [[Donald Trump]] at the [[2019 G20 Osaka summit|14th G20 in Osaka]], August 2019.]]\n{{Politics of China |expanded = Foreign }}\n\n'''China\u2013United States relations''' ({{zh|s={{linktext|\u4e2d\u7f8e|\u5173\u7cfb}} |t=\u4e2d\u7f8e\u95dc\u4fc2 |p=Zh\u014dngm\u011bi Gu\u0101nx\u00ec}}), also known as '''U.S.\u2013Chinese relations''', '''Chinese\u2013U.S. relations''', or '''Sino-American relations''', refers to [[international relations]] between [[China]] and the [[United States]]. The history of the relationship can be traced back to when the [[United States]] first gained independence. The relationship between the two countries have been, until recent years, quite strong, complex, and even somewhat positive in various aspects. Both countries used to have an extremely extensive economic partnership, and the great amount of trade between the two countries necessitated for constructive political relations, but significant issues still exist. The relationship is of economic cooperation, [[hegemony|hegemonic]] rivalry in the Pacific, and mutual suspicion over each other's intentions. Therefore, each nation has adopted a wary attitude regarding the other as a potential adversary but has meanwhile maintained an extremely strong economic partnership.<ref>Woon, C.Y., 2018. China\u2019s Contingencies: Critical Geopolitics, Chinese Exceptionalism and the Uses of History. Geopolitics, 23(1), pp.67-95.</ref> It has been described by world leaders and academics as the world's most important bilateral relationship of the 21st century.<ref>{{cite news| url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/americas/7891511.stm|work=BBC News|title=Clinton seeks stronger Asia ties|date=February 16, 2009 | accessdate=April 7, 2010}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://china.usc.edu/ShowArticle.aspx?articleID=1021&AspxAutoDetectCookieSupport=1|title=USC US-China Institute: Ambassador Clark Randt on \"The Crucial Relationship\"|publisher=China.usc.edu|accessdate=December 2, 2010|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090331163745/http://china.usc.edu/ShowArticle.aspx?articleID=1021&AspxAutoDetectCookieSupport=1|archivedate=March 31, 2009}}</ref>\n\n{{As of|2019}}, the [[United States]] has the world's [[List of countries by GDP (nominal)|largest economy]] and China has the [[List of countries by GDP (nominal)|second largest]] although China has a larger [[GDP]] when measured by [[Purchasing power parity|PPP]].<ref>{{cite web|title=World Economic Outlook|url=http://www.imf.org/external/pubs/ft/weo/2014/02/weodata/weorept.aspx?pr.x=33&pr.y=10&sy=2012&ey=2019&sort=country&ds=.&br=1&c=924%2C111&s=NGDPD%2CPPPGDP&grp=0&a=|website=International Monetary Fund|publisher=International Monetary Fund|accessdate=October 12, 2014}}</ref> Historically, relations between the two countries have generally been stable with some periods of open conflict, most notably during the [[Korean War]] and the [[Vietnam War]]. Currently, China and the United States have mutual political, economic, and security interests, such as the [[nuclear proliferation|proliferation of nuclear weapons]], but there are unresolved concerns relating to the role of [[democracy in China|democracy in government in China]] and [[human rights in China]]. China is the second largest foreign creditor of the United States, after [[Japan]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.scmp.com/business/companies/article/3023034/japan-overtakes-china-biggest-creditor-us-japans-june-treasuries|title=Japan surpasses China as the biggest creditor to the US government|date=2019-08-16|website=South China Morning Post|language=en|access-date=2019-08-18}}</ref> The two countries remain in dispute over [[South China Sea disputes|territorial issues in the South China Sea]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2016/07/15/world/asia/south-china-sea-dispute-arbitration-explained.html|title=The South China Sea: Explaining the Dispute|last=Fisher|first=Max|date=2016-07-14|work=The New York Times|access-date=2017-03-11|issn=0362-4331}}</ref>\n\nAccording to a 2017 [[BBC World Service]] poll, 33% of the Chinese view America's influence positively, and 61% express a negative view. Likewise, only 22% of Americans view China's influence positively, and 70% view it negatively.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.globescan.com/images/images/pressreleases/bbc2017_country_ratings/BBC2017_Country_Ratings_Poll.pdf|title=BBC World Service poll|last=|first=|date=30 June 2017|website=|publisher=BBC|access-date=2 March 2019}}</ref>\nAccording to a 2019 survey by the [[Pew Research Center]], 26% of Americans have a favorable view of China, with 60% expressing an unfavorable view.<ref name=\":0\">{{cite web|url=https://www.pewresearch.org/global/2019/08/13/u-s-views-of-china-turn-sharply-negative-amid-trade-tensions/|title=U.S. Views of China Turn Sharply Negative Amid Trade Tensions|publisher=Pew Research Center|date=August 13, 2019}}</ref> The poll also found that 24% of Americans see China as the top threat to the US.<ref name=\":0\" /> Relations with China began under US President [[George Washington]],<ref name=HistoryState/> leading to the 1845 [[Treaty of Wanghia|Treaty of Wangxia]]. The US was allied to the [[Republic of China (1912\u20131949)|Republic of China]] during the [[Pacific War]] but, after the [[Communist Party of China|Communist]] victory in [[Mainland China]] during the [[Chinese Civil War]], fought a major armed conflict with the People's Republic of China in the [[Korean War]] and did not establish relations for 25 years, until President [[Richard Nixon's 1972 visit to China]]. Since Nixon's visit, every US president, with the exception of [[Jimmy Carter]], has toured China. Relations with China have strained under President [[Barack Obama]]'s [[East Asian foreign policy of the Barack Obama administration|Asia pivot]] strategy and his support for Japan in the [[Senkaku Islands dispute]]. Despite tensions during his term, the Chinese population's favorability of the US stood at 51% in Obama's last year of 2016, only to dip during the [[Trump administration]].<ref>[https://www.pewresearch.org/global/database/indicator/1/country/cn/ Pew Global Indicators Database: China.]</ref>\n\nThe relations deteriorated sharply under President [[Donald Trump]],<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.aljazeera.com/blogs/asia/2019/05/china-trade-war-sino-american-ties-torn-brick-brick-190512132227395.html|title=China-US trade war: Sino-American ties being torn down brick by brick|website=www.aljazeera.com|access-date=2019-08-18}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.latimes.com/politics/la-na-pol-us-china-trade-stalemate-20190531-story.html|title=For the U.S. and China, it's not a trade war anymore \u2014 it's something worse|date=2019-05-31|website=Los Angeles Times|language=en-US|access-date=2019-08-18}}</ref> whose administration launched a [[China\u2013United States trade war|trade war against China]], banned US companies from selling equipment to [[Huawei]],<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.theverge.com/2018/8/13/17686310/huawei-zte-us-government-contractor-ban-trump|title=Trump signs bill banning government use of Huawei and ZTE tech|last=Kastrenakes|first=Jacob|date=2018-08-13|website=The Verge|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190529222201/https://www.theverge.com/2018/8/13/17686310/huawei-zte-us-government-contractor-ban-trump|archive-date=29 May 2019|access-date=2019-05-29}}</ref> increased visa restrictions on Chinese nationality students and scholars<ref name=\":02\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2019/04/14/world/asia/china-academics-fbi-visa-bans.html|title=F.B.I. Bars Some China Scholars From Visiting U.S. Over Spying Fears|last=Perlez|first=Jane|date=2019-04-14|work=The New York Times|access-date=2019-07-14|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2018/07/25/us/politics/visa-restrictions-chinese-students.html|title=Visa Restrictions for Chinese Students Alarm Academia|last=Yoon-Hendricks|first=Alexandra|date=2018-07-25|work=The New York Times|access-date=2019-07-14|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref> and designated China as a [[currency manipulator]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.cnbc.com/2019/08/06/trade-war-china-responds-to-us-after-claim-of-being-a-currency-manipulator.html|title=China responds to US after Treasury designates Beijing a 'currency manipulator'|last=Meredith|first=Sam|date=2019-08-06|website=CNBC|language=en|access-date=2019-08-06}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.ft.com/content/9d24c1ca-b7cd-11e9-96bd-8e884d3ea203|title=Subscribe to read|website=Financial Times|language=en-GB|access-date=2019-08-06}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.channelnewsasia.com/news/singapore/ndr-2019-singapore-will-be-principled-in-approach-to-china-us-11819238|title=NDR 2019: Singapore will be 'principled' in approach to China-US trade dispute; ready to help workers|website=CNA|language=en|access-date=2019-08-18}}</ref> During the Trump administration, and especially since the US-China trade war began, political observers have started to warn that a [[Cold War II#Sino-American tensions|new cold war]] is emerging.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.ft.com/content/a3062586-a9ac-11e9-984c-fac8325aaa04|title=Subscribe to read|website=Financial Times|language=en-GB|access-date=2019-08-18}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.worldpoliticsreview.com/articles/27975/why-a-cold-war-with-china-would-be-so-costly|title=Why a Cold War With China Would Be So Costly|website=www.worldpoliticsreview.com|access-date=2019-08-18}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.scmp.com/news/china/diplomacy/article/3022587/china-us-cold-war-inevitable-chinese-analysts-say-it-cant-be|title=Is China-US cold war inevitable? Chinese analysts say it can't be ruled out|date=2019-08-14|website=South China Morning Post|language=en|access-date=2019-08-18}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.aljazeera.com/indepth/opinion/cold-war-africa-190630102044847.html|title=A new cold war in Africa|last=Maru|first=Mehari Taddele|website=www.aljazeera.com|access-date=2019-08-18}}</ref> [[Michael D. Swaine]] warned in 2019, \"The often positive and optimistic forces, interests, and beliefs that sustained bilateral ties for decades are giving way to undue pessimism, hostility, and a zero-sum mindset in almost every area of engagement.\"<ref>Michael D Swaine, [https://carnegieendowment.org/2019/01/16/relationship-under-extreme-duress-u.s.-china-relations-at-crossroads-pub-78159  \"A Relationship Under Extreme Duress: U.S.-China Relations at a Crossroads\" ''Carnegie Endowment for International Peace'' (Jan. 16, 2019)]</ref> However by 2020, the two countries have started to take steps to repair the relations; the US lifted its [[currency manipulator]] designation on China on 13 January 2020, and both countries signed the US\u2013China Phase One trade deal on 15 January.\n\n==Country comparison==\n{| class=\"wikitable mw-collapsible mw-collapsed\"\n|-\n! Common name !! [[China]] !! [[United States]]\n|-\n! Official name !! People's Republic of China!! United States of America\n|-\n| Flag\n| style=\"text-align:center\" |{{Flagicon|China|size=125px|text=none}}\n| style=\"text-align:center\" |{{Flagicon|America|size=155px|text=none}}\n|-\n| Coat of arms\n| style=\"text-align:center\" | [[File:National Emblem of the People's Republic of China (2).svg|140px]]\n| style=\"text-align:center\" | [[File:Great Seal of the United States (obverse).svg|145px]]\n|-\n| [[List of countries and dependencies by area|Area]]\n| 9,596,961&nbsp;km\u00b2 (3,705,407 sq mi)\n(including [[Hong Kong]] and [[Macau]])\n|9,525,067&nbsp;km\u00b2 (3,677,649 sq mi)<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.britannica.com/place/United-States|title=United States {{!}} History, Map, Flag, & 