eyman]]) vs. [[Drew McIntyre]]\n|stip3  = [[Singles match (professional wrestling)|Singles match]] for the [[WWE Championship]]<ref>{{cite web|last1=Chik|first1=Jon|title=WWE Champion Brock Lesnar vs. Drew McIntyre|url=https://www.wwe.com/shows/wrestlemania/wrestlemania-36/brock-lesnar-vs-drew-mcintyre|work=WWE|accessdate=January 27, 2020}}</ref>\n|time3  = \u2013\n|match4 = [[John Cena]] vs. [[Bray Wyatt|\"The Fiend\" Bray Wyatt]]\n|stip4  = [[No Holds Barred match|Firefly Fun House match]]<ref>{{cite web|title=John Cena vs. \"The Fiend\" Bray Wyatt|url=https://www.wwe.com/shows/wrestlemania/wrestlemania-36/john-cena-vs-the-fiend-bray-wyatt|work=WWE|accessdate=February 28, 2020}}</ref>\n|time4  = \u2013\n|match5 = [[Bayley (wrestler)|Bayley]] (c) vs. [[Lacey Evans]] vs. [[Naomi (wrestler)|Naomi]] vs. [[Sasha Banks]] vs. [[Tamina Snuka|Tamina]]\n|stip5  = [[Professional wrestling match types#Basic elimination matches|Fatal 5-Way Elimination match]] for the [[WWE SmackDown Women's Championship]]<ref>{{cite web|title=SmackDown Women\u2019s Champion Bayley vs. Sasha Banks vs. Lacey Evans vs. Tamina vs. Naomi (WrestleMania Fatal 5-Way Elimination Match)|url=https://www.wwe.com/shows/wrestlemania/wrestlemania-36/six-pack-challenge-elimination-match|work=WWE|date=March 20, 2020|accessdate=March 20, 2020}}</ref>\n|time5  = \u2013\n|match6 = [[The Street Profits]] (Angelo Dawkins and Montez Ford) (c) vs. [[Austin Theory]] and [[Angel Garza]] (with [[Zelina Vega]])\n|stip6  = [[Tag team match]] for the [[WWE Raw Tag Team Championship]]<ref>{{cite web|title=Raw Tag Team Champions The Street Profits vs. Austin Theory & Angel Garza|url=https://www.wwe.com/shows/wrestlemania/wrestlemania-36/the-street-profits-vs-austin-theory-angel-garza|work=WWE|date=March 31, 2020|accessdate=March 31, 2020}}</ref>\n|time6  = \u2013\n|match7 = [[Aleister Black]] vs. [[Bobby Lashley]] (with [[Lana (wrestler)|Lana]]) \n|stip7  = [[Singles match]]<ref>{{cite web|last1=Benigno|first1=Anthony|title=Aleister Black vs. Bobby Lashley|url=https://www.wwe.com/shows/wrestlemania/wrestlemania-36/aleister-black-vs-bobby-lashley|work=WWE|accessdate=March 23, 2020}}</ref>\n|time7  = \u2013\n|match8 = [[Edge (wrestler)|Edge]] vs. [[Randy Orton]]\n|stip8  = [[Last Man Standing match]]<ref>{{cite web|last1=Garretson|first1=Jordan|title=Edge vs. Randy Orton (Last Man Standing Match)|url=https://www.wwe.com/shows/wrestlemania/wrestlemania-36/edge-vs-randy-orton|work=WWE|accessdate=March 23, 2020}}</ref>\n|time8  = \u2013\n|match9 = [[Otis Dozovic|Otis]] (with [[Tucker]]) vs. [[Dolph Ziggler]] (with [[Mandy Rose]])\n|stip9  = [[Singles match (professional wrestling)|Singles match]]<ref>{{cite web|last1=Chik|first1=John|title=Otis vs. Dolph Ziggler|url=https://www.wwe.com/shows/wrestlemania/wrestlemania-36/otis-vs-dolph-ziggler|work=WWE|date=March 30, 2020|accessdate=March 30, 2020}}</ref>\n|time9  = \u2013\n}}\n\n== Notes ==\n{{reflist|group=Note}}\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n\n* [https://m.imdb.com/title/tt9363602/ WrestleMania 36]  on [[IMDb]]\n\n* {{Official website|http://www.wwe.com/shows/wrestlemania|WrestleMania official website}}\n\n{{2020 WWE Network events}}\n{{WWEPPV|WrestleMania}}\n\n[[Category:2020 WWE Network events]]\n[[Category:2020 WWE pay-per-view events]]\n[[Category:2020 in Florida]]\n[[Category:Professional wrestling in Orlando, Florida]]\n[[Category:Events in Orlando, Florida]]\n[[Category:April 2020 events in the United States]]\n[[Category:WrestleMania]]\n[[Category:Scheduled professional wrestling shows]]\n[[Category:Impact of the 2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic on television]]\n", "name_user": "NotTheFakeJTP", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eResults", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/WrestleMania_36"}
{"title_page": "George Henry Peters", "text_new": "[[File:George Henry Peters g109B.jpg|thumb|upright=0.9|George Henry Peters (approx. 1920)]]\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\" align=\"right\" style=\"margin: 1em; margin-top: 0; font-size: 0.9em;\"\n|+ [[Asteroid]]s discovered: 3&thinsp;<ref name=\"MPC-Discoverers\" />\n|-\n| [[536 Merapi]] || May 11, 1904 || {{MPC|536}}\n|-\n| [[886 Washingtonia]] || November 16, 1917 || {{MPC|886}}\n|-\n| [[980 Anacostia]] || November 21, 1921 || {{MPC|980}}\n|}\n\n'''George Henry Peters''' (1863\u2013October 18, 1947) was a US [[astronomer]] and a [[discoverer of minor planets]].<ref name=\"MPC-Discoverers\" />\n\nHe worked at the [[U.S. Naval Observatory]] as an astrophotographer, discovering three [[asteroid]]s and photographing the [[Sun]]'s [[solar corona|corona]].{{citation needed|date=April 2013}} He died in Washington, D.C.\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist\n|refs=\n\n<ref name=\"MPC-Discoverers\">{{cite web\n  |title      = Minor Planet Discoverers (by number)\n  |work       = Minor Planet Center\n  |url        = http://www.minorplanetcenter.net/iau/lists/MPDiscsNum.html\n  |date       = 20 June 2016\n  |accessdate = 15 August 2016}}</ref>\n\n}} <!-- end of reflist -->\n\n== External links ==\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20070313105356/http://cache.corbis.com/agent/11/49/88/11498891.jpg Corbis photo with caption]: ''Dr. George Henry Peters, of the U.S. Naval Observatory at Washington, with the 46 inch (1.2 m) lens, weighing 150 pounds (68 kg) and capable of taking a photo 195,000,000 miles (314,000,000 km) <!-- what does that mean? --> away, which is to be used to photograph total eclipse of sun on January 24.'']\n\n=== Obituary ===\n* [http://adsabs.harvard.edu//full/seri/PASP./0059//0000344.000.html PASP '''59''' (1947) 344] (one paragraph)\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Peters, George Henry}}\n[[Category:1863 births]]\n[[Category:1947 deaths]]\n[[Category:American astronomers]]\n[[Category:Discoverers of asteroids]]\n[[Category:Discoveries by George Peters|*]]\n[[Category:American people of Dutch descent]]\n\n\n{{US-astronomer-stub}}\n", "text_old": "[[File:George Henry Peters g109B.jpg|thumb|upright=0.9|George Henry Peters (approx. 1920)]]\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\" align=\"right\" style=\"margin: 1em; margin-top: 0; font-size: 0.9em;\"\n|+ [[Asteroid]]s discovered: 3&thinsp;<ref name=\"MPC-Discoverers\" />\n|-\n| [[536 Merapi]] || May 11, 1904 || {{MPC|536}}\n|-\n| [[886 Washingtonia]] || November 16, 1917 || {{MPC|886}}\n|-\n| [[980 Anacostia]] || November 21, 1921 || {{MPC|980}}\n|}\n\n'''George Henry Peters''' (1863\u2013October 18, 1947) was a US [[astronomer]] and a [[discoverer of minor planets]].<ref name=\"MPC-Discoverers\" />\n\nHe worked at the [[U.S. Naval Observatory]] as an astrophotographer, discovering three [[asteroid]]s and photographing the [[Sun]]'s [[corona]].{{citation needed|date=April 2013}} He died in Washington, D.C.\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist\n|refs=\n\n<ref name=\"MPC-Discoverers\">{{cite web\n  |title      = Minor Planet Discoverers (by number)\n  |work       = Minor Planet Center\n  |url        = http://www.minorplanetcenter.net/iau/lists/MPDiscsNum.html\n  |date       = 20 June 2016\n  |accessdate = 15 August 2016}}</ref>\n\n}} <!-- end of reflist -->\n\n== External links ==\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20070313105356/http://cache.corbis.com/agent/11/49/88/11498891.jpg Corbis photo with caption]: ''Dr. George Henry Peters, of the U.S. Naval Observatory at Washington, with the 46 inch (1.2 m) lens, weighing 150 pounds (68 kg) and capable of taking a photo 195,000,000 miles (314,000,000 km) <!-- what does that mean? --> away, which is to be used to photograph total eclipse of sun on January 24.'']\n\n=== Obituary ===\n* [http://adsabs.harvard.edu//full/seri/PASP./0059//0000344.000.html PASP '''59''' (1947) 344] (one paragraph)\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Peters, George Henry}}\n[[Category:1863 births]]\n[[Category:1947 deaths]]\n[[Category:American astronomers]]\n[[Category:Discoverers of asteroids]]\n[[Category:Discoveries by George Peters|*]]\n[[Category:American people of Dutch descent]]\n\n\n{{US-astronomer-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Netoholic", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200etop:post-move link fix", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/George_Henry_Peters"}
{"title_page": "Love Under New Management", "text_new": "{{Infobox song\n| name       = Love Under New Management\n| cover      = Miki Howard - Love Under New Management.jpg\n| alt        =\n| type       = single\n| artist     = [[Miki Howard]]\n| album      = [[Miki Howard (album)|Miki Howard]]\n| B-side     = [[Come Share My Love (song)|Come Share My Love]]\n| released   = December 21, 1989\n| format     =\n| recorded   =\n| studio     =\n| venue      =\n| genre      =\n| length     = 6:46\n| label      = [[Atlantic Records|Atlantic Records (Warner)]]\n| writer     = [[Gabriel Hardeman]] Annette Hardeman and G Syier Hawkins Brown\n| producer   = [[Nick Martinelli]]\n| prev_title = [[Ain't Nuthin' in the World]]\n| prev_year  = 1989\n| next_title = [[Until You Come Back to Me (That's What I'm Gonna Do)#Cover versions|Until You Come Back to Me (That's What I'm Gonna Do)]]\n| next_year  = 1990\n}}\n\n\"'''Love Under New Management'''\" is the second single released from the 1989 [[Miki Howard (album)|self-titled album]] by American [[R&B]] singer [[Miki Howard]]. The song reached its peak of No. 2 on Billboard's [[Hot R&B Singles]] chart on March 24, 1990.<ref>http://www.billboard.com/charts/1990-03-24/r-b-hip-hop-songs</ref> The song held that position for two weeks (kept out of the top spot by \"[[All Around the World (Lisa Stansfield song)|All Around the World]]\" by [[Lisa Stansfield]]) and propelled the album to No. 4 on the [[Top R&B Albums]] chart, Howard's highest charting album.<ref name=miki>{{cite web|url={{BillboardURLbyName|artist=miki howard|chart=all}} |title=Love Under New Management - Miki Howard |publisher=Billboard.com |date=1990-03-24 |accessdate=2011-04-22}}</ref> The song reached #89 on Billboard's Hot 100 chart.\n\nThe music video for the single was directed by a then-unknown [[Mark Romanek]], who also directed the video for her cover of [[Aretha Franklin]]'s song \"''[[Until You Come Back to Me (That's What I'm Gonna Do)]]''\".<ref>http://www.people.com/people/archive/article/0,,20117682,00.html</ref>\n\n==Charts==\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n!align=\"left\"|Chart (1990) \n!align=\"center\"|Peak<br>position\n|-\n|align=\"left\"|U.S. ''[[Billboard Hot 100|''Billboard'' Hot 100]]'' \n|align=\"center\"|89\n|-\n|-\n|align=\"left\"|U.S. ''Billboard'' [[Hot R&B Singles]]\n|align=\"center\"|2\n|}\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Miki Howard}}\n[[Category:1990 singles]]\n[[Category:Miki Howard songs]]\n[[Category:Song recordings produced by Nick Martinelli]]\n[[Category:1990 songs]]\n[[Category:Atlantic Records singles]]\n[[Category:Keke Wyatt songs]]\n[[Category:2011 songs]]\n\n{{1990s-R&B-song-stub}}\n[[Category:Music videos directed by Mark Romanek]]\n[[Category:1980s ballads]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox song\n| name       = Love Under New Management\n| cover      = Miki Howard - Love Under New Management.jpg\n| alt        =\n| type       = single\n| artist     = [[Miki Howard]]\n| album      = [[Miki Howard (album)|Miki Howard]]\n| B-side     = [[Come Share My Love (song)|Come Share My Love]]\n| released   = December 21, 1989\n| format     =\n| recorded   =\n| studio     =\n| venue      =\n| genre      =\n| length     = 6:46\n| label      = [[Atlantic Records|Atlantic Records (Warner)]]\n| writer     = [[Gabriel Hardeman]] and Annette Hardeman\n| producer   = [[Nick Martinelli]]\n| prev_title = [[Ain't Nuthin' in the World]]\n| prev_year  = 1989\n| next_title = [[Until You Come Back to Me (That's What I'm Gonna Do)#Cover versions|Until You Come Back to Me (That's What I'm Gonna Do)]]\n| next_year  = 1990\n}}\n\n\"'''Love Under New Management'''\" is the second single released from the 1989 [[Miki Howard (album)|self-titled album]] by American [[R&B]] singer [[Miki Howard]]. The song reached its peak of No. 2 on Billboard's [[Hot R&B Singles]] chart on March 24, 1990.<ref>http://www.billboard.com/charts/1990-03-24/r-b-hip-hop-songs</ref> The song held that position for two weeks (kept out of the top spot by \"[[All Around the World (Lisa Stansfield song)|All Around the World]]\" by [[Lisa Stansfield]]) and propelled the album to No. 4 on the [[Top R&B Albums]] chart, Howard's highest charting album.<ref name=miki>{{cite web|url={{BillboardURLbyName|artist=miki howard|chart=all}} |title=Love Under New Management - Miki Howard |publisher=Billboard.com |date=1990-03-24 |accessdate=2011-04-22}}</ref> The song reached #89 on Billboard's Hot 100 chart.\n\nThe music video for the single was directed by a then-unknown [[Mark Romanek]], who also directed the video for her cover of [[Aretha Franklin]]'s song \"''[[Until You Come Back to Me (That's What I'm Gonna Do)]]''\".<ref>http://www.people.com/people/archive/article/0,,20117682,00.html</ref>\n\n==Charts==\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n!align=\"left\"|Chart (1990) \n!align=\"center\"|Peak<br>position\n|-\n|align=\"left\"|U.S. ''[[Billboard Hot 100|''Billboard'' Hot 100]]'' \n|align=\"center\"|89\n|-\n|-\n|align=\"left\"|U.S. ''Billboard'' [[Hot R&B Singles]]\n|align=\"center\"|2\n|}\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Miki Howard}}\n[[Category:1990 singles]]\n[[Category:Miki Howard songs]]\n[[Category:Song recordings produced by Nick Martinelli]]\n[[Category:1990 songs]]\n[[Category:Atlantic Records singles]]\n[[Category:Keke Wyatt songs]]\n[[Category:2011 songs]]\n\n{{1990s-R&B-song-stub}}\n[[Category:Music videos directed by Mark Romanek]]\n[[Category:1980s ballads]]\n", "name_user": "Drgsyierb", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Love_Under_New_Management"}
{"title_page": "Sunspot (comics)", "text_new": "{{In-universe|date=October 2018}}\n{{Infobox comics character <!--Wikipedia:WikiProject Comics-->\n|image=Roberto da Costa.jpg\n|caption=Roberto da Costa as seen in ''[[The New Avengers (comic book)|The New Avengers]]'' #14 (July [[2016 in comics|2016]]).<br />Art by Paco Medina.\n|character_name=Sunspot\n|real_name=Roberto da Costa\n|species=[[Mutant (Marvel Comics)|Human Mutant]]\n|publisher=[[Marvel Comics]]\n|debut=''[[The New Mutants (graphic novel)|The New Mutants]]'' (September [[1982 in comics|1982]])\n|creators=[[Chris Claremont]]<br />[[Bob McLeod (comics)|Bob McLeod]]\n|alliances= [[New Mutants]]<br />[[Avengers (comics)|Avengers]]<br />[[Advanced Idea Mechanics|A.I.M.]]<br />Costa International<br />[[Fallen Angels (comics)|Fallen Angels]]<br />[[Hellfire Club (comics)|Hellfire Club]]<br />[[Mutant Liberation Front]]<br />[[The New Avengers (comics)|New Avengers]]<br />[[X-Corporation]]<br />[[X-Force]]<br />[[X-Men]]<br />[[Young X-Men]]<br />[[U.S.Avengers]]<br />[[S.H.I.E.L.D.]]\n|aliases=Lord Imperial, Black Rook, Black King, [[Citizen V]]\n|powers=Superhuman strength<br />Flight<br />Solar absorption and rechanneling<br />Heat and light manipulation<br />Concussive blasts<br />Plasma emission\n}}\n\n'''Sunspot''' ('''Roberto da Costa''') is a fictional [[superhero]] appearing in [[American comic book]]s published by [[Marvel Comics]]. The character is most commonly associated with [[X-Men]]-related groups the [[New Mutants]] and [[X-Force]].\n\nA [[Mutant (Marvel Comics)|mutant]] from [[Brazil]], Sunspot possesses the ability to absorb and channel [[solar power]]. He is idealistic and impulsive, but is considered a close friend of many of his teammates. He was an important member of the X-Men's 1980s-era junior team and its reincarnation X-Force. He later retired his career as Sunspot and garnered a massive fortune, allowing him to buy out the organization [[Advanced Idea Mechanics]], rebranding it Avengers Idea Mechanics, which he operates under the codename '''[[Citizen V]]'''.\n\nIn film, actor [[Adan Canto]] portrayed the character in ''[[X-Men: Days of Future Past (film)|X-Men: Days of Future Past]]''. [[Henry Zaga]] will portray a younger version in ''[[The New Mutants (film)|The New Mutants]]''.\n\n==Publication history==\n{{Expand section|date=April 2010}}\n[[image:XMN Sunspot.jpg|thumb|150px|Sunspot.<br/> Art by [[Diogenes Neves]].]]\nCreated by writer [[Chris Claremont]] and artist [[Bob McLeod (comics)|Bob McLeod]], Sunspot first appeared in ''[[The New Mutants (graphic novel)|The New Mutants]]'' (Nov 1982), part of the [[line (comics)|line]] ''[[Marvel Graphic Novel]]''.<ref>{{cite book |last1=DeFalco |first1=Tom |last2=Sanderson |first2=Peter |last3=Brevoort |first3=Tom |last4=Teitelbaum |first4=Michael |last5=Wallace |first5=Daniel |last6=Darling |first6=Andrew |last7=Forbeck |first7=Matt |last8=Cowsill |first8=Alan |last9=Bray |first9=Adam |title=The Marvel Encyclopedia |date=2019 |publisher=DK Publishing |isbn=978-1-4654-7890-0 |page=364}}</ref> Immediately following, he became part of the regular cast of ''[[The New Mutants (comic book)|The New Mutants]]'', as part of the titular supergroup.\n\nHe was a member of the Avengers in the 2012 relaunch of the ''Avengers'' title.\n\nSunspot is one of the main characters in ''[[U.S.Avengers]]''.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.cbr.com/marvel-gets-patriotic-with-u-s-avengers-series-from-ewing-medina/|title=Marvel Gets Patriotic with \"U.S.Avengers\" Series from Ewing &amp; Medina|date=2016-07-01|website=CBR|language=en-US|access-date=2019-08-21}}</ref>\n\n==Fictional character biography==\n\n===Origin===\nSunspot, or Roberto da Costa, is Brazilian, the son of wealthy Afro-Brazilian businessman Emmanuel da Costa and his white American mother archaeologist Nina da Costa. In ''New Mutants'' #7, his father is described as a very driven man, who \"grew up [...] a barefoot houseboy\", \"by age 20 [...] a millionaire [and] by 30, an economic and political force to be reckoned with.\" Emmanuel constantly pushes his son to reach for both his physical and intellectual limits. Thanks to his father's encouragement, Roberto rose to the position of star [[soccer]] player at school<ref name=MGN4>''Marvel Graphic Novel'' #4</ref> and was considered by recruiters for the [[Olympic Games]].\n\nWhen Roberto was playing a soccer game with his team, racist members of the opposing team assaulted him, and Roberto responded by initiating a fight on the field. While taking a brutal beating, his mutant powers manifested, suddenly transforming him into a creature of solid black solar energy. Surprised and terrified, people abandoned the stadium, and only his girlfriend Juliana refused to abandon him.<ref name=MGN4 />\n\n===New Mutants===\n<!-- Deleted image removed: [[Image:Marfan027sun.jpg|150px|thumb|left|Sunspot in his original outfit from ''Marvel Fanfare #27''. Art By Bob McLeod]] -->\nWithin a matter of days, a mutant-hating faction led by [[Donald Pierce]] and employing [[Hellfire Club (comics)|Hellfire Club]] mercenaries kidnap Juliana, luring Roberto into a trap. He engages the [[Reavers (comics)|kidnappers]], but is eventually defeated when his power reserve runs out. Other mutants named [[Karma (comics)|Karma]] and [[Danielle Moonstar|Psyche]] rescue him. In the course of the following battle, Juliana sacrifices her life for Roberto, jumping in front of a bullet meant for him.<ref name=\"MGN4\"/>\n\nAfter the rescue, Roberto joins Karma and Psyche in pursuit of Donald Pierce. The three are joined by [[Wolfsbane (comics)|Wolfsbane]], and after the battle by Sam Guthrie, a.k.a. [[Cannonball (comics)|Cannonball]], one of Pierce's misguided mutant hirelings, despite initial reservations by the others. [[Professor X]] offers to train the five teenagers in controlling their nascent mutant powers, which they accept and thus become the founding members of the group known as the [[New Mutants]], a group of junior [[X-Men]].<ref name=\"MGN4\"/> Although [[Professor Xavier]]'s intentions are for them to only be students, over the course of the ''New Mutants'' ongoing series, they grow into superheroes, and they travel to such locations as space, Asgard, and the Amazon, as well as the past and the future. During his tenure with the New Mutants, he and Sam become best friends.\n\nSunspot was at one point injected with the drug that helped create [[Cloak and Dagger (comics)|Cloak and Dagger]], and he briefly became a monster.<ref>''Marvel Team-Up Annual'' #6</ref> Sunspot was later reunited with his parents, and then with the New Mutants he visited Nova Roma.<ref>''New Mutants'' #9\u201311</ref> He then encountered the [[Emma Frost|White Queen]] and her [[Hellions (Marvel Comics)|Hellions]] for the first time.<ref>''New Mutants'' #16\u201317</ref> He was later abducted and forced to serve as one of the Gladiators.<ref>''New Mutants'' #29\u201331</ref> On another adventure with the New Mutants, he visited the land of [[Asgard (comics)|Asgard]].<ref>''New Mutants Special Edition'' #1; ''Uncanny X-Men Annual'' #9</ref> Alongside the New Mutants, he later fought [[Warlock (New Mutants)|Warlock]]'s father, the [[Magus (Technarchy)|Magus]].<ref>''New Mutants'' #50</ref> He also battled [[Cameron Hodge]] and the [[Right (comics)|Right]].<ref>''New Mutants'' #60</ref> Alongside the New Mutants he battled [[Freedom Force (comics)|Freedom Force]].<ref name=\"New Mutants #65\">''New Mutants'' #65</ref> He also fell in love with the alien [[Gosamyr]].<ref name=\"New Mutants #65\"/>\n\n===X-Force===\n<!-- Image with inadequate rationale removed: [[Image:xforce46.jpg|150px|thumb|Cover to ''X-Force'' #46 featuring Sunspot and [[Mimic (comics)|Mimic]].]]  -->\nWhen the [[time travel]]ing [[antihero]] [[Cable (comics)|Cable]] takes over the New Mutants and turns them into the [[paramilitary]] group X-Force, Sunspot parts ways with the team.<ref>''New Mutants'' vol.1 #99</ref> During this time Sunspot is tutored by [[Gideon (comics)|Gideon]] of the [[Externals]], an old business partner of Roberto's father (who has since died). Suspecting Sunspot to be a fellow External, he takes Sunspot under his wing.<ref>''New Mutants'' #98</ref> Gideon ends up experimenting on Sunspot, granting him new powers such as flight and the ability to fire blasts of solar energy.<ref>''X-Force'' #14\u201317</ref> For a time Sunspot becomes lost in a [[space-time continuum]] after interfering with the [[teleportation]] powers of [[Locus (comics)|Locus]].<ref>''X-Force'' #28</ref> During this time, a villain called [[Reignfire]] comes onto the scene, showing a remarkable similar appearance to Sunspot.<ref>''X-Force'' #28 (1993) through ''X-Force'' #43 (1995)</ref>\n\n===Reignfire===\n{{Main|Reignfire}}\nThe villain Reignfire first appears <ref>''X-Force'' #26 (1993)</ref> before Sunspot's mysterious disappearance in ''X-Force'' #28 (1993), when he assumes command of the [[Mutant Liberation Front]].  [[Dani Moonstar]], who had infiltrated the MLF, sees Reignfire without his mask and believes him to be Sunspot,<ref>''X-Force'' Annual #3 (1994)</ref> and in a battle with X-Force, Reignfire even removes his mask to reveal himself as Sunspot.<ref>''X-Force'' #43 (1995)</ref> The moment was interrupted by the [[Age of Apocalypse]]<ref>Occurring between ''X-Force'' #43 and #44 (1995)</ref> and when reality is restored, Cable 'heals' Sunspot of this persona dominating his body,<ref>Off panel between ''X-Force'' #43 and 44 (1995)</ref> transferring some of his [[Askani]] knowledge into Sunspot, allowing Sunspot to speak the Askani language and know of their meditation techniques.<ref>''Cable'' vol. 1 #29 (1996)</ref> In an incident where X-Force reconnected with former teammate [[Skids (comics)|Skids]], it is discovered that Reignfire is actually a protoplasmic mutant symbiote injected with Sunspot's blood.<ref>''X-Force'' #78-80 (1998)</ref> Reignfire is seemingly permanently defeated when Sunspot leeches him of his powers, reducing him to his original protoplasmic state which is then claimed by [[S.H.I.E.L.D.]]<ref>''X-Force'' #80 (1998)</ref>\n\n===X-Force Roadtrip===\nRoberto later joins the rest of X-Force on an extended road trip, separating themselves from Cable. Along the way, they meet several problems, including Roberto's money being tied up in litigation, forcing the team into doing a variety of odd jobs. One included providing protection for a small businessman being hassled by elements of the mob. During this time, Roberto has a short fling with Sam's girlfriend [[Tabitha Smith]], a teammate.<ref>''X-Force'' #75\u201392</ref>\n\n===Hellfire Club===\nLater during his X-Force career, Roberto is approached by [[Selene (comics)|Selene]] of the [[Hellfire Club (comics)|Hellfire Club]]. She offers Roberto his deceased father Emmanuel's seat in the Club's Inner Circle, as the seats are inherited.<ref>''X-Force'' vol. 1 #94, 97</ref>  She promises Roberto that she will resurrect Juliana if he joins and he agrees.{{Issue|date=January 2012}} Selene keeps her part of the bargain, but only to a certain extent. She does bring back the spirit of Juliana, but inserts it into the body of a [[coma]]tose girl.{{Issue|date=January 2012}} Possibly because he felt obliged to fulfill his promise, Roberto decides to stay, becoming Selene's Black Rook.{{Issue|date=January 2012}}  Roberto attempts to contact the resurrected Juliana, but seeing she has no memory of her previous life, he decides to leave her alone.<ref>''X-Force'' vol. 1 #98\u2013100</ref>\n\nWith no explanation given, Roberto next surfaces in the title ''X-Treme X-Men'' as the head of the [[Los Angeles]] branch of [[X-Corporation]], along with former New Mutant [[Magma (comics)|Magma]] and former [[Hellions (Marvel Comics)|Hellion]] [[Empath (comics)|Empath]].{{Issue|date=January 2012}} Roberto's ties to the Hellfire Club are not however severed, as [[Sebastian Shaw (comics)|Sebastian Shaw]] approaches, having taken over the position of Hellfire Club's Lord Imperial and wanting Roberto as his Black King. Shaw claims that he is trying to turn the Club into a force of good, so Roberto accepts, though he keeps his involvement with Shaw a secret.{{Issue|date=March 2011}}\n\nSoon after, Shaw is injured in battle by Donald Pierce.{{Issue|date=January 2012}} His injuries make him incapable of overseeing the Hellfire Club. Roberto takes over as Lord Imperial.{{Issue|date=January 2012}} At his side is  [[Sage (comics)|Sage]] who leaves the X-Men to make sure Roberto is not corrupted by the power he wields.{{Issue|date=January 2012}} After the events of [[Decimation (comics)|M-Day]], [[Cyclops (Marvel Comics)|Cyclops]] calls for the shutting down of all branches of the X-Corporation to better pool the resources of the X-Men.{{Issue|date=January 2012}} In [[X-Men: Endangered Species|Endangered Species]], Sebastian Shaw seems to be thinking of reclaiming his place and to be quite mad at Sunspot.{{Issue|date=March 2011}}\n\n===Secret Invasion===\nDuring the ''[[Secret Invasion]]'' storyline, Sunspot is among the several X-Men helping to fight off Skrulls during their invasion of San Francisco.<ref>''Secret Invasion: X-Men'' #1</ref>\n\n===Young X-Men===\nSunspot, who remains Lord Imperial of the Hellfire Club, is revealed by Cyclops to belong to the newest incarnation of the [[Brotherhood of Evil Mutants]] along with [[Danielle Moonstar]], Cannonball, and Magma.<ref>''Young X-Men'' #1</ref> However, while battling members of Cyclops' new team of [[Young X-Men|X-Men]] alongside Cannonball, there is much confusion after [[Rockslide (comics)|Rockslide]] makes reference to the two mutants' membership in the Brotherhood.  During the course of the battle, Sunspot is seriously wounded by [[Wolf Cub (comics)|Wolf Cub]], who slashes Roberto's face and stomach with his claws.<ref>''Young X-Men'' #3</ref>  It is eventually revealed that \"Cyclops\" is in reality [[Donald Pierce]], the former White King of the Hellfire Club, who is posing as the X-Men leader using an image inducer.<ref>''Young X-Men'' #4</ref>  Pierce's reasons for recruiting these \"X-Men\" is currently unknown, but it appears that his primary focus is to eliminate the Lord Imperial and utilized the ruse that Sunspot and his allies formed a new Brotherhood in order to convince the former [[X-Mansion|Xavier students]] to attack their former teachers and allies.\n\nLater on, Sunspot leaves the Hellfire Club and joins the X-Men in San Francisco as noted by Sebastian Shaw who is currently looking for a replacement. Cyclops later asks Sunspot and Danielle Moonstar to help train the [[Young X-Men]] and both accepted.<ref>''Young X-Men'' #6</ref>\n\n===Reforming the New Mutants===\nAfter receiving an anonymous tip in Colorado about a young mutant endangering a small town, Dani and Shan are sent to investigate and calm the locals. During their mission, Magik reappears back at the X-Men's base in San Francisco after teleporting off into the future after the events of \"X-Infernus\". Upon her return she informs Sam and Roberto that Shan and Dani are in trouble and it will result in their deaths. Sam assembles a team consisting of himself, Sunspot, Magma, and Magik to go find them. While searching for them, Sam and Roberto come across a tied up and comatose Shan in the back of a bar, while Magik and Magma are tricked into freeing [[Legion (Marvel Comics)|Legion]] from a box, who apparently has Shan's personality imprisoned inside of him.<ref>''New Mutants'' vol. 3 #1</ref> Roberto and Sam approach Karma's body but when Roberto gets too close he almost gets pulled into Legion's mind. After they leave the bar, they find they're surrounded by police; Roberto and Sam fly away to the jail to find Dani.<ref>''New Mutants'' vol. 3 #2</ref>\n\nWhen they arrive, Legion is trying to kill Dani. After Roberto and Sam repel him, Legion comes back and Sunspot fights him. Cannonball soon joins him and they fend him off and regroup.<ref>''New Mutants'' vol. 3 #3</ref> During the fight, Legion takes on Magma, Cannonball, and Roberto, who gets seriously injured when Legion slashes him with a shard of metal.<ref>''New Mutants'' vol. 3 #4</ref>\n\n===[[The New Avengers (comics)#Volume 4 (2015\u20132016)|New Avengers]]===\nAfter the events of ''[[Avengers vs. X-Men]]'', Roberto and Sam are shown retired, no longer wishing to protect those that fear and hate them. The two are then offered membership in the [[The New Avengers (comics)|Avengers]] by [[Captain America]] and eagerly accept, realizing that this may be a chance to save the world without suffering from the stigma they did while serving as X-Men.<ref>''Avengers'' vol. 5 #2</ref> As revealed in a storyline that takes place eight months in the future, Roberto engages in a hostile takeover of the violent company [[Advanced Idea Mechanics]] and gets rid of the troublesome upper management.<ref>''Avengers'' #35 (Sept. 2014)</ref> He re-tools this into Avengers Idea Mechanics, hiring various superheroes as a new Avengers team consisting of Hawkeye, Songbird, Squirrel Girl, Hulking, Wiccan, Power Man and White Tiger. S.H.I.E.L.D. sends two operatives, [[Dum Dum Dugan]] and Hawkeye to keep on eye on the team. Despite orders to spy on the new A.I.M., both men reveal their mission as they have come to respect Sunspot.<ref>''New Avengers'' #1\u20133 (2015)</ref> His new team has annoyed the [[Maker (Reed Richards)|Maker]], the [[Ultimate Universe]]'s version of [[Mister Fantastic|Reed Richards]]. The Maker's various plans cause trouble for the Avengers that bounces up and down the time stream.<ref>''New Avengers'' #4\u20135 (2016)</ref>\n\n===U.S.Avengers===\nFollowing the deal that would get the Avengers Idea Mechanics to merge with the U.S. government as the American Intelligence Mechanics, Sunspot began to lead the [[U.S.Avengers]] under the alias of [[Citizen V]].<ref>''U.S. Avengers'' #1</ref> Their first mission takes place at the [[Secret Empire (organization)|Secret Empire]]'s floating volcanic island base. [[Robert Maverick|Red Hulk]] crash-landed into the floating volcanic island base, hard enough to destroy it. They're later approached by a future version of [[Danielle Cage]] as Captain America, who tells them that her nemesis, the Golden Skull, came to their timeline to steal all the wealth. In [[Miami, Florida]], the team crash a charity gala only to discover that the wealthy CEO's were kidnapped and replaced by robots. During the battle, the team manages to defeat and capture the Golden Skull, who was wearing a golden armored suit. Danielle then goes back to her timeline with the Golden Skull as her prisoner. Sunspot then sends Red Hulk to confront and defeat an out-of-control American Kaiju, who was attacking [[Europe]].<ref>''U.S. Avengers'' #2-4</ref>\n\nDuring the \"Opening Salvo\" part of the ''[[Secret Empire (comic book)|Secret Empire]]'' storyline, Captain America, whose memory was altered by Red Skull's clone using the powers of [[Kobik]], has a meeting with Roberto da Costa and tells him that he is no longer in charge of the team. Roberto then sees footage of the supervillain attacks in Manhattan, deep space, and in Europe.<ref>''U.S.Avengers'' #5</ref> At the beginning of the takeover, Roberto assembles the team until he is attacked by one of his scientists who has allied with [[Hydra (comics)|Hydra]]. He's later seen in a prison cell, nearly dead, by Red Hulk and [[Iron Patriot|Toni Ho]]. While adjusting to prison life, Toni manages to heal Roberto just in time when Hydra soldiers show up at their cell. Roberto then manages to use his powers to defeat the guards and free Red Hulk from the nanites controlling him, allowing them to take control of the prison.<ref>''U.S.Avengers'' #6-9</ref> In the aftermath of the event, Roberto, during a meeting with the team's new congressional liaison in the White House, resigns from his position despite the objections from the senator. He then meets [[Smasher (comics)|Izzy Kane]], [[Cannonball]]'s wife, who tells him that Cannonball, who went missing in action during the takeover and was presumed dead, is still alive on another planet.<ref>''U.S.Avengers'' #10</ref>\n\nWhile travelling through space, Smasher and the U.S.Avengers are attacked by space pirates known as warpjackers. After a brief fight, the pirates tell them that Glenbrook is actually a planet named Kral X and that its ruler, Ritchie Redwood, is ruthless.<ref>''U.S.Avengers'' #11</ref> Arriving in Kral X, the heroes manage to help Cannonball and the planet's rebels in overthrowing Ritchie. After restoring order to the planet, the heroes head home.<ref>''U.S.Avengers'' #12</ref>\n\n===[[War of the Realms]]===\n\nAfter the Age of X-Man removes most X-Men members to an alternate reality, Sunspot reappears to assist [[Dani Moonstar|Mirage]] and the remaining X-Men repel Malekith's invasion of Midgard.<ref>Uncanny X-Men: War of the Realms #2 (2019)</ref> In a ploy to allow [[Magik (comics)|Magik]] to teleport the invading horde to Limbo, he breaks a cursed amulet blocking her powers, and in doing so, is vaporized, joining the fallen Valkyries in their journey to the afterlife.<ref>Uncanny X-Men: War of the Realms #3 (2019)</ref>\n\n==Powers and abilities==\n[[Image:XMEN SunspotPowerup.jpg|thumb|right|200px|Sunspot's energized state.<br/>''New Mutants'' #6<br/>Art by [[Diogenes Neves]].]]\nSunspot is a [[Mutant (Marvel Comics)|mutant]] whose cells have the ability to absorb [[solar energy]] and convert it for use as physical strength. He is also able to create thermal updrafts for flight, project heat and light, as well as concussive blasts of solar energy.<ref>{{Cite book|title=Marvel Encyclopedia: Updated and Expanded|last=|first=|publisher=|year=|isbn=|location=|pages=}}</ref> At will, he is able to take on a superhuman \"powered up\" form that is entirely nonreflective black, save for his eyes which turn a solid bright white. Though the color black optimizes solar absorption, he absorbs solar power at all times, not only when he is in his \"powered up\" form. If he has not absorbed sufficient amounts of solar energy in normal form, he will be too weak to \"power up\". Likewise, when not in direct sunlight, use of his superhuman strength rapidly exhausts the stores of energy within his body.<ref>{{cite journal|last=Buchanan|first=Bruce |title=The New Mutants: From Superhero Spin-Off to Sci-Fi/Fantasy|journal=[[Back Issue!]]|issue=29 |page=63|publisher=[[TwoMorrows Publishing]]|date=August 2008|location=Raleigh, North Carolina}}</ref>\n\nWhen in his solar form, Sunspot also has a [[solar corona|corona]] effect, an aura that has been depicted in multiple ways, though two predominant conventions exist for its portrayal: one is that the air close to him manifests black globes of various sizes, reminiscent of [[Kirby dots]], and the other is a unified field glowing a bright yellow or white.  Although Sunspot can absorb energy from stars and reflected solar energy from the moon, the amounts that reach him on Earth are too minuscule to add significantly to his power. In other regions, such as [[Asgard (comics)|Asgard]], his power is significantly enhanced, allowing him - with much effort - to lift [[Volstagg]] off the ground for a few seconds before suffering a backache.<ref>''New Mutants Special Edition'' #1 (Dec. 1985)</ref>\n\nOriginally, Sunspot's superhuman power was limited solely to superhuman strength and enhanced durability, and then only in his solar form. Unlike many superhumanly strong heroes, Sunspot was unique in that his physical resistance to impact only increased somewhat when he employed his superhuman strength, and he was not bulletproof by any means. The phrase, \"Careful Bobby, you're strong, not invulnerable!\" or variations was seen many times. In addition, Sunspot's powers have radically changed and grown since the character was introduced; he can now withstand the force of a speeding eighteen-wheeler traveling at speeds of 100&nbsp;mph. Alongside surviving an A.I.M explosive charge latched onto his side.<ref>''Avengers World'' Vol. 1 #18</ref>\n\nSunspot maintained his original powerset for roughly the first ten years of his existence, remaining a super strong but vulnerable individual throughout the entire ''New Mutants'' series. During the mid-1990s in ''X-Force'' his powers began to change, under writer [[Fabian Nicieza]]. Nicieza had the supervillain Gideon capture Roberto and subject him to experimentation where the limits of Roberto's power absorption were tested by feeding him immense amounts of solar power. Roberto was rescued by X-Force, but the overload had permanently altered his powers in such a way that he was now able to release concussive blasts of solar energy, with a considerable heat and light projection component; this experimentation also made him immune to all types of heat and fire. He can also now absorb other forms of energy; such as heat, light or even radiation in a manner similar to photo/radio- or thermokinesis, It was believed they do not power up his abilities but this was proven false.<ref>''Hulk'' Vol 3 #3</ref><ref name=\"Avengers World Vol. 1 #19\">''Avengers World'' Vol. 1 #19</ref> Sunspot also has some capacity to manipulate light based energy effects, but it remains a largely unexplored portent of his mutant power.<ref name=\"Avengers World Vol. 1 #19\"/> It has been debated that Roberto would have reached these levels of his abilities of his own accord, and that Gideon's experimentation only increased his evolution process.\n\nThe fact that the solar blasts were concussive in origin led directly into ''X-Force'' #28, where Sunspot thinks of using them as a means of propulsion, and thus fly by blasting in the opposite direction of where he wanted to go \u2013 initially leaving a slight trail behind him, but in later years, Roberto would learn to use the propulsion more subtly \u2013 to appear to hover in place with no blast wake at all other than his usual \"powered up\" corona effect. His capacity to fly has similarly been enhanced as he is able to breach planetary orbit and reach Saturn's belt with relative ease.<ref>''Hulk'' Vol 3 #3-4</ref>\n\nSunspot also had the rituals and ideas of the [[Askani]] inside his head, due to a telepathic contact with Cable. While being strongly influenced by it for a while, the memories seem to have faded.\n\nSignificant non-superhuman abilities include business administration, as he owns and runs a multibillion-dollar international conglomerate. He is an Olympic-class athlete as the result of having been trained in combat by the X-Men and later by Cable. He is an expert in many languages (see below) and has an assortment of other more minor talents such as piloting aircraft. He was trained in swordsmanship by the Gladiators, and is also an excellent soccer player.\n\n==Other versions==\n\n===Age of Apocalypse===\nSunspot was in the X-Ternals with [[Jubilee (comics)|Jubilee]], [[Strong Guy]], and [[Gambit (comics)|Gambit]]. Like [[Robin Hood]], they take money from [[Apocalypse (comics)|Apocalypse]] and give to the poor. [[Magneto (Marvel Comics)|Magneto]] assigns them to travel to the [[Shi'ar]] Galaxy to steal the powerful [[M'Kraan Crystal]].<ref>''Gambit and the X-Ternals'' #1\u20134 (1995\u201396)</ref> Sunspot dies after absorbing too much energy in an attempt to help his teammates escape.{{issue|date=June 2017}}\n\n===Days of Future Now===\nIn this reality, Sunspot is shown as the leader of the [[Gene Nation]].{{Issue|date=March 2010}}\n\n===Mutant X===\nSunspot is part of a murderous team of '[[Marauders (comics)#Mutant X|Marauders]]', which consists of [[Jubilee (comics)|Jubilee]], [[Wolfsbane (comics)|Wolfsbane]], [[Cannonball (comics)|Cannonball]], and [[Husk (comics)|Husk]].{{Issue|date=May 2009}}\n\n===Ultimate Marvel===\nThe [[Ultimate Marvel]] version of Sunspot a.k.a. Roberto da Costa is an angry vigilante mutant of Brazilian descent. Originally came from Harlem in this continuity, he sees the [[Ultimate X-Men|X-Men]] as decadent [[Uncle Tom]] figures and has accused them of living in an ivory tower, considering themselves separate from \"second-class muties\" like himself. He also harbors a deep hatred for [[Magneto (Marvel Comics)|Magneto]] and his followers because of the anti-mutant hysteria that followed the Brooklyn Bridge's destruction at the [[Brotherhood of Evil Mutants]]'s hands.{{Issue|date=March 2010}}\n\nAfterward he has joined Emma Frost's [[New Mutants|Academy of Tomorrow]], a school for gifted beings. Initially, Roberto is confused as he knows his grades are not impressive. Emma assures him that grades (or even mutant powers) do not always classify a person as 'gifted'.{{Issue|date=March 2010}} Soon after Roberto is accepted into the school, he is in trouble: fellow student [[Polaris (Marvel Comics)|Lorna Dane]] is framed and imprisoned for the murder of several dozen people.  He is approached by Alex Summers (Polaris's boyfriend) and is convinced to help assist in breaking Lorna out. He works with [[Northstar (Marvel Comics)|Northstar]] and [[Cannonball (comics)|Cannonball]]. The team relies on Roberto's knowledge of New York City, but because Roberto had rarely been ''outside'' of Harlem, this reliance results in the team becoming lost. During this time, the X-Men attack them, and Roberto is subdued and removed from the fight.{{issue|date=March 2016}}\n\nMagneto has him killed in Ultimatum along with the rest of the Academy of Tomorrow except for [[Havok (comics)|Havok]].{{Issue|date=April 2009}} Sunspot is murdered in an attack.{{Issue|date=March 2010}} He is buried on the grounds of the [[X-Mansion]].<ref>''[[Ultimate Requiem]]''</ref>\n\n===What If?===\nIn \"What if Some of the X-Men Had Stayed In Asgard?\", Sunspot is one of the X-Men and New Mutants members who choose to remain in Asgard. When [[Hela (comics)|Hela]] attacks [[Storm (Marvel Comics)|Storm]] due to [[Loki (comics)|Loki]]'s intrigues, Sunspot rushes to aid Storm, to have his life taken away by the death goddess before he can land a blow on her.<ref>''What If?'' vol.2 #12</ref>\n\n==In other media==\n\n===Television===\n[[File:Sunspot-film.jpg|right|thumb|150px|[[Adan Canto]] as Sunspot in ''[[X-Men: Days of Future Past]]''.]]\n* Sunspot appears in ''[[X-Men: Evolution]]'', voiced by Michael Coleman. Depicted as seventeen-year-old boy, this version is a member of a junior team of X-Men. Born in Brazil, he moved to [[Xavier's School for Gifted Youngsters]], together with the other recruits, at Professor X's request. This version is something of a showoff, and sometimes gets into fights with his teammates, especially [[Berzerker (comics)|Berzerker]].\n\n===Film===\n* Sunspot was originally meant to appear in ''[[X-Men: First Class]]'', but was written out because of time and budget issues.<ref>{{cite web| url= http://www.bleedingcool.com/2011/05/24/matthew-vaughn-on-x-men-first-class-on-the-writing-credits-on-the-bond-influence-on-the-difficult-shoot-and-more/ | title= Matthew Vaughn On X-Men: First Class \u2013 On The Writing Credits, On The Bond Influence, On The Difficult Shoot And More| date= May 24, 2011 |first= Brendon |last= Connelly | website= BleedingCool.com| accessdate= March 12, 2016}}</ref>\n* Sunspot appears in ''[[X-Men: Days of Future Past]]'', portrayed by [[Adan Canto]].<ref>{{cite web|url= http://www.digitalspy.com/movies/news/a494134/x-men-days-of-future-past-adan-canto-confirms-sunspot-role.html |first= Hugh| last= Armitage| date= June 28, 2013| title= 'X-Men: Days of Future Past': Adan Canto confirms Sunspot role| website= DigitalSpy.com| accessdate= March 12, 2016}}</ref> This incarnation possesses a solar fiery aura, solar-powered flight and strength, and the ability to project solar energy and fire blasts. At film's beginning, Sunspot attempts to stall the advanced [[Sentinel (comics)|Sentinels]] so [[Kitty Pryde]] and [[Bishop (comics)|Bishop]] could change the past, but has his neck snapped by a Sentinel while in his solar form. During the battle, one Sentinel mimics Sunspot's powers in order to adapt to [[Iceman (Marvel Comics)|Iceman]]'s abilities, overcoming and killing him. Sunspot fought the Sentinels again so that [[Wolverine (character)|Wolverine]] could change the past. These events are erased later in the film's plot, after Wolverine's success in changing the events of decades-previous that lead to the Sentinels' creation.\n* Sunspot will appear in ''[[The New Mutants (film)|The New Mutants]]'', portrayed by [[Henry Zaga]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/heat-vision/fault-stars-writers-tackling-x-922893|title='Fault in Our Stars' Writers Tackling 'X-Men' Spinoff 'New Mutants' (Exclusive)|website=The Hollywood Reporter|language=en|access-date=2019-08-21}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://screenrant.com/deadpool-2-casting-x-force-sunspot-feral-shatterstar/|title=Deadpool 2 Is Bringing In More X-Force Characters|date=2017-05-09|website=ScreenRant|language=en-US|access-date=2019-08-21}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.tracking-board.com/stranger-things-star-charlie-heaton-to-play-cannonball-in-new-mutants/|title=\"STRANGER THINGS\" STAR CHARLIE HEATON TO PLAY CANNONBALL IN \"NEW MUTANTS\"|last=Sneider|first=Jeff|work=The Tracking Board|date=May 31, 2017|accessdate=May 31, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://collider.com/new-mutants-movie-cannonball-charlie-heaton/|title='New Mutants' Finds Its Cannonball with 'Stranger Things' Star Charlie Heaton|last=Goldberg|first=Matt|work=Collider|date=May 31, 2017|access-date=May 31, 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170601012439/http://collider.com/new-mutants-movie-cannonball-charlie-heaton/|archive-date=June 1, 2017|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist|2}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://marvel.com/universe/Sunspot Sunspot] at Marvel.com\n* [http://uncannyxmen.net/characters/sunspot Spotlight On Sunspot], UncannyXmen.net\n{{X-Men}}\n{{New Mutants}}\n{{X-Force}}\n{{Ultimate X-Men}}\n{{Avengers}}\n{{Portal bar|Speculative fiction|Brazil|1980s}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Sunspot (Comics)}}\n[[Category:American superheroes]]\n[[Category:Brazilian superheroes]]\n[[Category:Characters created by Bob McLeod]]\n[[Category:Characters created by Chris Claremont]]\n[[Category:Comics characters introduced in 1982]]\n[[Category:Fictional Brazilian people of American descent]]\n[[Category:Fictional Brazilian people of African descent]]\n[[Category:Fictional businesspeople]]\n[[Category:Fictional characters with fire or heat abilities]]\n[[Category:Male characters in comics]]\n[[Category:Marvel Comics characters with superhuman strength]]\n[[Category:Marvel Comics male superheroes]]\n[[Category:Marvel Comics mutants]]\n[[Category:S.H.I.E.L.D. agents]]\n[[Category:X-Men supporting characters]]\n", "text_old": "{{In-universe|date=October 2018}}\n{{Infobox comics character <!--Wikipedia:WikiProject Comics-->\n|image=Roberto da Costa.jpg\n|caption=Roberto da Costa as seen in ''[[The New Avengers (comic book)|The New Avengers]]'' #14 (July [[2016 in comics|2016]]).<br />Art by Paco Medina.\n|character_name=Sunspot\n|real_name=Roberto da Costa\n|species=[[Mutant (Marvel Comics)|Human Mutant]]\n|publisher=[[Marvel Comics]]\n|debut=''[[The New Mutants (graphic novel)|The New Mutants]]'' (September [[1982 in comics|1982]])\n|creators=[[Chris Claremont]]<br />[[Bob McLeod (comics)|Bob McLeod]]\n|alliances= [[New Mutants]]<br />[[Avengers (comics)|Avengers]]<br />[[Advanced Idea Mechanics|A.I.M.]]<br />Costa International<br />[[Fallen Angels (comics)|Fallen Angels]]<br />[[Hellfire Club (comics)|Hellfire Club]]<br />[[Mutant Liberation Front]]<br />[[The New Avengers (comics)|New Avengers]]<br />[[X-Corporation]]<br />[[X-Force]]<br />[[X-Men]]<br />[[Young X-Men]]<br />[[U.S.Avengers]]<br />[[S.H.I.E.L.D.]]\n|aliases=Lord Imperial, Black Rook, Black King, [[Citizen V]]\n|powers=Superhuman strength<br />Flight<br />Solar absorption and rechanneling<br />Heat and light manipulation<br />Concussive blasts<br />Plasma emission\n}}\n\n'''Sunspot''' ('''Roberto da Costa''') is a fictional [[superhero]] appearing in [[American comic book]]s published by [[Marvel Comics]]. The character is most commonly associated with [[X-Men]]-related groups the [[New Mutants]] and [[X-Force]].\n\nA [[Mutant (Marvel Comics)|mutant]] from [[Brazil]], Sunspot possesses the ability to absorb and channel [[solar power]]. He is idealistic and impulsive, but is considered a close friend of many of his teammates. He was an important member of the X-Men's 1980s-era junior team and its reincarnation X-Force. He later retired his career as Sunspot and garnered a massive fortune, allowing him to buy out the organization [[Advanced Idea Mechanics]], rebranding it Avengers Idea Mechanics, which he operates under the codename '''[[Citizen V]]'''.\n\nIn film, actor [[Adan Canto]] portrayed the character in ''[[X-Men: Days of Future Past (film)|X-Men: Days of Future Past]]''. [[Henry Zaga]] will portray a younger version in ''[[The New Mutants (film)|The New Mutants]]''.\n\n==Publication history==\n{{Expand section|date=April 2010}}\n[[image:XMN Sunspot.jpg|thumb|150px|Sunspot.<br/> Art by [[Diogenes Neves]].]]\nCreated by writer [[Chris Claremont]] and artist [[Bob McLeod (comics)|Bob McLeod]], Sunspot first appeared in ''[[The New Mutants (graphic novel)|The New Mutants]]'' (Nov 1982), part of the [[line (comics)|line]] ''[[Marvel Graphic Novel]]''.<ref>{{cite book |last1=DeFalco |first1=Tom |last2=Sanderson |first2=Peter |last3=Brevoort |first3=Tom |last4=Teitelbaum |first4=Michael |last5=Wallace |first5=Daniel |last6=Darling |first6=Andrew |last7=Forbeck |first7=Matt |last8=Cowsill |first8=Alan |last9=Bray |first9=Adam |title=The Marvel Encyclopedia |date=2019 |publisher=DK Publishing |isbn=978-1-4654-7890-0 |page=364}}</ref> Immediately following, he became part of the regular cast of ''[[The New Mutants (comic book)|The New Mutants]]'', as part of the titular supergroup.\n\nHe was a member of the Avengers in the 2012 relaunch of the ''Avengers'' title.\n\nSunspot is one of the main characters in ''[[U.S.Avengers]]''.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.cbr.com/marvel-gets-patriotic-with-u-s-avengers-series-from-ewing-medina/|title=Marvel Gets Patriotic with \"U.S.Avengers\" Series from Ewing &amp; Medina|date=2016-07-01|website=CBR|language=en-US|access-date=2019-08-21}}</ref>\n\n==Fictional character biography==\n\n===Origin===\nSunspot, or Roberto da Costa, is Brazilian, the son of wealthy Afro-Brazilian businessman Emmanuel da Costa and his white American mother archaeologist Nina da Costa. In ''New Mutants'' #7, his father is described as a very driven man, who \"grew up [...] a barefoot houseboy\", \"by age 20 [...] a millionaire [and] by 30, an economic and political force to be reckoned with.\" Emmanuel constantly pushes his son to reach for both his physical and intellectual limits. Thanks to his father's encouragement, Roberto rose to the position of star [[soccer]] player at school<ref name=MGN4>''Marvel Graphic Novel'' #4</ref> and was considered by recruiters for the [[Olympic Games]].\n\nWhen Roberto was playing a soccer game with his team, racist members of the opposing team assaulted him, and Roberto responded by initiating a fight on the field. While taking a brutal beating, his mutant powers manifested, suddenly transforming him into a creature of solid black solar energy. Surprised and terrified, people abandoned the stadium, and only his girlfriend Juliana refused to abandon him.<ref name=MGN4 />\n\n===New Mutants===\n<!-- Deleted image removed: [[Image:Marfan027sun.jpg|150px|thumb|left|Sunspot in his original outfit from ''Marvel Fanfare #27''. Art By Bob McLeod]] -->\nWithin a matter of days, a mutant-hating faction led by [[Donald Pierce]] and employing [[Hellfire Club (comics)|Hellfire Club]] mercenaries kidnap Juliana, luring Roberto into a trap. He engages the [[Reavers (comics)|kidnappers]], but is eventually defeated when his power reserve runs out. Other mutants named [[Karma (comics)|Karma]] and [[Danielle Moonstar|Psyche]] rescue him. In the course of the following battle, Juliana sacrifices her life for Roberto, jumping in front of a bullet meant for him.<ref name=\"MGN4\"/>\n\nAfter the rescue, Roberto joins Karma and Psyche in pursuit of Donald Pierce. The three are joined by [[Wolfsbane (comics)|Wolfsbane]], and after the battle by Sam Guthrie, a.k.a. [[Cannonball (comics)|Cannonball]], one of Pierce's misguided mutant hirelings, despite initial reservations by the others. [[Professor X]] offers to train the five teenagers in controlling their nascent mutant powers, which they accept and thus become the founding members of the group known as the [[New Mutants]], a group of junior [[X-Men]].<ref name=\"MGN4\"/> Although [[Professor Xavier]]'s intentions are for them to only be students, over the course of the ''New Mutants'' ongoing series, they grow into superheroes, and they travel to such locations as space, Asgard, and the Amazon, as well as the past and the future. During his tenure with the New Mutants, he and Sam become best friends.\n\nSunspot was at one point injected with the drug that helped create [[Cloak and Dagger (comics)|Cloak and Dagger]], and he briefly became a monster.<ref>''Marvel Team-Up Annual'' #6</ref> Sunspot was later reunited with his parents, and then with the New Mutants he visited Nova Roma.<ref>''New Mutants'' #9\u201311</ref> He then encountered the [[Emma Frost|White Queen]] and her [[Hellions (Marvel Comics)|Hellions]] for the first time.<ref>''New Mutants'' #16\u201317</ref> He was later abducted and forced to serve as one of the Gladiators.<ref>''New Mutants'' #29\u201331</ref> On another adventure with the New Mutants, he visited the land of [[Asgard (comics)|Asgard]].<ref>''New Mutants Special Edition'' #1; ''Uncanny X-Men Annual'' #9</ref> Alongside the New Mutants, he later fought [[Warlock (New Mutants)|Warlock]]'s father, the [[Magus (Technarchy)|Magus]].<ref>''New Mutants'' #50</ref> He also battled [[Cameron Hodge]] and the [[Right (comics)|Right]].<ref>''New Mutants'' #60</ref> Alongside the New Mutants he battled [[Freedom Force (comics)|Freedom Force]].<ref name=\"New Mutants #65\">''New Mutants'' #65</ref> He also fell in love with the alien [[Gosamyr]].<ref name=\"New Mutants #65\"/>\n\n===X-Force===\n<!-- Image with inadequate rationale removed: [[Image:xforce46.jpg|150px|thumb|Cover to ''X-Force'' #46 featuring Sunspot and [[Mimic (comics)|Mimic]].]]  -->\nWhen the [[time travel]]ing [[antihero]] [[Cable (comics)|Cable]] takes over the New Mutants and turns them into the [[paramilitary]] group X-Force, Sunspot parts ways with the team.<ref>''New Mutants'' vol.1 #99</ref> During this time Sunspot is tutored by [[Gideon (comics)|Gideon]] of the [[Externals]], an old business partner of Roberto's father (who has since died). Suspecting Sunspot to be a fellow External, he takes Sunspot under his wing.<ref>''New Mutants'' #98</ref> Gideon ends up experimenting on Sunspot, granting him new powers such as flight and the ability to fire blasts of solar energy.<ref>''X-Force'' #14\u201317</ref> For a time Sunspot becomes lost in a [[space-time continuum]] after interfering with the [[teleportation]] powers of [[Locus (comics)|Locus]].<ref>''X-Force'' #28</ref> During this time, a villain called [[Reignfire]] comes onto the scene, showing a remarkable similar appearance to Sunspot.<ref>''X-Force'' #28 (1993) through ''X-Force'' #43 (1995)</ref>\n\n===Reignfire===\n{{Main|Reignfire}}\nThe villain Reignfire first appears <ref>''X-Force'' #26 (1993)</ref> before Sunspot's mysterious disappearance in ''X-Force'' #28 (1993), when he assumes command of the [[Mutant Liberation Front]].  [[Dani Moonstar]], who had infiltrated the MLF, sees Reignfire without his mask and believes him to be Sunspot,<ref>''X-Force'' Annual #3 (1994)</ref> and in a battle with X-Force, Reignfire even removes his mask to reveal himself as Sunspot.<ref>''X-Force'' #43 (1995)</ref> The moment was interrupted by the [[Age of Apocalypse]]<ref>Occurring between ''X-Force'' #43 and #44 (1995)</ref> and when reality is restored, Cable 'heals' Sunspot of this persona dominating his body,<ref>Off panel between ''X-Force'' #43 and 44 (1995)</ref> transferring some of his [[Askani]] knowledge into Sunspot, allowing Sunspot to speak the Askani language and know of their meditation techniques.<ref>''Cable'' vol. 1 #29 (1996)</ref> In an incident where X-Force reconnected with former teammate [[Skids (comics)|Skids]], it is discovered that Reignfire is actually a protoplasmic mutant symbiote injected with Sunspot's blood.<ref>''X-Force'' #78-80 (1998)</ref> Reignfire is seemingly permanently defeated when Sunspot leeches him of his powers, reducing him to his original protoplasmic state which is then claimed by [[S.H.I.E.L.D.]]<ref>''X-Force'' #80 (1998)</ref>\n\n===X-Force Roadtrip===\nRoberto later joins the rest of X-Force on an extended road trip, separating themselves from Cable. Along the way, they meet several problems, including Roberto's money being tied up in litigation, forcing the team into doing a variety of odd jobs. One included providing protection for a small businessman being hassled by elements of the mob. During this time, Roberto has a short fling with Sam's girlfriend [[Tabitha Smith]], a teammate.<ref>''X-Force'' #75\u201392</ref>\n\n===Hellfire Club===\nLater during his X-Force career, Roberto is approached by [[Selene (comics)|Selene]] of the [[Hellfire Club (comics)|Hellfire Club]]. She offers Roberto his deceased father Emmanuel's seat in the Club's Inner Circle, as the seats are inherited.<ref>''X-Force'' vol. 1 #94, 97</ref>  She promises Roberto that she will resurrect Juliana if he joins and he agrees.{{Issue|date=January 2012}} Selene keeps her part of the bargain, but only to a certain extent. She does bring back the spirit of Juliana, but inserts it into the body of a [[coma]]tose girl.{{Issue|date=January 2012}} Possibly because he felt obliged to fulfill his promise, Roberto decides to stay, becoming Selene's Black Rook.{{Issue|date=January 2012}}  Roberto attempts to contact the resurrected Juliana, but seeing she has no memory of her previous life, he decides to leave her alone.<ref>''X-Force'' vol. 1 #98\u2013100</ref>\n\nWith no explanation given, Roberto next surfaces in the title ''X-Treme X-Men'' as the head of the [[Los Angeles]] branch of [[X-Corporation]], along with former New Mutant [[Magma (comics)|Magma]] and former [[Hellions (Marvel Comics)|Hellion]] [[Empath (comics)|Empath]].{{Issue|date=January 2012}} Roberto's ties to the Hellfire Club are not however severed, as [[Sebastian Shaw (comics)|Sebastian Shaw]] approaches, having taken over the position of Hellfire Club's Lord Imperial and wanting Roberto as his Black King. Shaw claims that he is trying to turn the Club into a force of good, so Roberto accepts, though he keeps his involvement with Shaw a secret.{{Issue|date=March 2011}}\n\nSoon after, Shaw is injured in battle by Donald Pierce.{{Issue|date=January 2012}} His injuries make him incapable of overseeing the Hellfire Club. Roberto takes over as Lord Imperial.{{Issue|date=January 2012}} At his side is  [[Sage (comics)|Sage]] who leaves the X-Men to make sure Roberto is not corrupted by the power he wields.{{Issue|date=January 2012}} After the events of [[Decimation (comics)|M-Day]], [[Cyclops (Marvel Comics)|Cyclops]] calls for the shutting down of all branches of the X-Corporation to better pool the resources of the X-Men.{{Issue|date=January 2012}} In [[X-Men: Endangered Species|Endangered Species]], Sebastian Shaw seems to be thinking of reclaiming his place and to be quite mad at Sunspot.{{Issue|date=March 2011}}\n\n===Secret Invasion===\nDuring the ''[[Secret Invasion]]'' storyline, Sunspot is among the several X-Men helping to fight off Skrulls during their invasion of San Francisco.<ref>''Secret Invasion: X-Men'' #1</ref>\n\n===Young X-Men===\nSunspot, who remains Lord Imperial of the Hellfire Club, is revealed by Cyclops to belong to the newest incarnation of the [[Brotherhood of Evil Mutants]] along with [[Danielle Moonstar]], Cannonball, and Magma.<ref>''Young X-Men'' #1</ref> However, while battling members of Cyclops' new team of [[Young X-Men|X-Men]] alongside Cannonball, there is much confusion after [[Rockslide (comics)|Rockslide]] makes reference to the two mutants' membership in the Brotherhood.  During the course of the battle, Sunspot is seriously wounded by [[Wolf Cub (comics)|Wolf Cub]], who slashes Roberto's face and stomach with his claws.<ref>''Young X-Men'' #3</ref>  It is eventually revealed that \"Cyclops\" is in reality [[Donald Pierce]], the former White King of the Hellfire Club, who is posing as the X-Men leader using an image inducer.<ref>''Young X-Men'' #4</ref>  Pierce's reasons for recruiting these \"X-Men\" is currently unknown, but it appears that his primary focus is to eliminate the Lord Imperial and utilized the ruse that Sunspot and his allies formed a new Brotherhood in order to convince the former [[X-Mansion|Xavier students]] to attack their former teachers and allies.\n\nLater on, Sunspot leaves the Hellfire Club and joins the X-Men in San Francisco as noted by Sebastian Shaw who is currently looking for a replacement. Cyclops later asks Sunspot and Danielle Moonstar to help train the [[Young X-Men]] and both accepted.<ref>''Young X-Men'' #6</ref>\n\n===Reforming the New Mutants===\nAfter receiving an anonymous tip in Colorado about a young mutant endangering a small town, Dani and Shan are sent to investigate and calm the locals. During their mission, Magik reappears back at the X-Men's base in San Francisco after teleporting off into the future after the events of \"X-Infernus\". Upon her return she informs Sam and Roberto that Shan and Dani are in trouble and it will result in their deaths. Sam assembles a team consisting of himself, Sunspot, Magma, and Magik to go find them. While searching for them, Sam and Roberto come across a tied up and comatose Shan in the back of a bar, while Magik and Magma are tricked into freeing [[Legion (Marvel Comics)|Legion]] from a box, who apparently has Shan's personality imprisoned inside of him.<ref>''New Mutants'' vol. 3 #1</ref> Roberto and Sam approach Karma's body but when Roberto gets too close he almost gets pulled into Legion's mind. After they leave the bar, they find they're surrounded by police; Roberto and Sam fly away to the jail to find Dani.<ref>''New Mutants'' vol. 3 #2</ref>\n\nWhen they arrive, Legion is trying to kill Dani. After Roberto and Sam repel him, Legion comes back and Sunspot fights him. Cannonball soon joins him and they fend him off and regroup.<ref>''New Mutants'' vol. 3 #3</ref> During the fight, Legion takes on Magma, Cannonball, and Roberto, who gets seriously injured when Legion slashes him with a shard of metal.<ref>''New Mutants'' vol. 3 #4</ref>\n\n===[[The New Avengers (comics)#Volume 4 (2015\u20132016)|New Avengers]]===\nAfter the events of ''[[Avengers vs. X-Men]]'', Roberto and Sam are shown retired, no longer wishing to protect those that fear and hate them. The two are then offered membership in the [[The New Avengers (comics)|Avengers]] by [[Captain America]] and eagerly accept, realizing that this may be a chance to save the world without suffering from the stigma they did while serving as X-Men.<ref>''Avengers'' vol. 5 #2</ref> As revealed in a storyline that takes place eight months in the future, Roberto engages in a hostile takeover of the violent company [[Advanced Idea Mechanics]] and gets rid of the troublesome upper management.<ref>''Avengers'' #35 (Sept. 2014)</ref> He re-tools this into Avengers Idea Mechanics, hiring various superheroes as a new Avengers team consisting of Hawkeye, Songbird, Squirrel Girl, Hulking, Wiccan, Power Man and White Tiger. S.H.I.E.L.D. sends two operatives, [[Dum Dum Dugan]] and Hawkeye to keep on eye on the team. Despite orders to spy on the new A.I.M., both men reveal their mission as they have come to respect Sunspot.<ref>''New Avengers'' #1\u20133 (2015)</ref> His new team has annoyed the [[Maker (Reed Richards)|Maker]], the [[Ultimate Universe]]'s version of [[Mister Fantastic|Reed Richards]]. The Maker's various plans cause trouble for the Avengers that bounces up and down the time stream.<ref>''New Avengers'' #4\u20135 (2016)</ref>\n\n===U.S.Avengers===\nFollowing the deal that would get the Avengers Idea Mechanics to merge with the U.S. government as the American Intelligence Mechanics, Sunspot began to lead the [[U.S.Avengers]] under the alias of [[Citizen V]].<ref>''U.S. Avengers'' #1</ref> Their first mission takes place at the [[Secret Empire (organization)|Secret Empire]]'s floating volcanic island base. [[Robert Maverick|Red Hulk]] crash-landed into the floating volcanic island base, hard enough to destroy it. They're later approached by a future version of [[Danielle Cage]] as Captain America, who tells them that her nemesis, the Golden Skull, came to their timeline to steal all the wealth. In [[Miami, Florida]], the team crash a charity gala only to discover that the wealthy CEO's were kidnapped and replaced by robots. During the battle, the team manages to defeat and capture the Golden Skull, who was wearing a golden armored suit. Danielle then goes back to her timeline with the Golden Skull as her prisoner. Sunspot then sends Red Hulk to confront and defeat an out-of-control American Kaiju, who was attacking [[Europe]].<ref>''U.S. Avengers'' #2-4</ref>\n\nDuring the \"Opening Salvo\" part of the ''[[Secret Empire (comic book)|Secret Empire]]'' storyline, Captain America, whose memory was altered by Red Skull's clone using the powers of [[Kobik]], has a meeting with Roberto da Costa and tells him that he is no longer in charge of the team. Roberto then sees footage of the supervillain attacks in Manhattan, deep space, and in Europe.<ref>''U.S.Avengers'' #5</ref> At the beginning of the takeover, Roberto assembles the team until he is attacked by one of his scientists who has allied with [[Hydra (comics)|Hydra]]. He's later seen in a prison cell, nearly dead, by Red Hulk and [[Iron Patriot|Toni Ho]]. While adjusting to prison life, Toni manages to heal Roberto just in time when Hydra soldiers show up at their cell. Roberto then manages to use his powers to defeat the guards and free Red Hulk from the nanites controlling him, allowing them to take control of the prison.<ref>''U.S.Avengers'' #6-9</ref> In the aftermath of the event, Roberto, during a meeting with the team's new congressional liaison in the White House, resigns from his position despite the objections from the senator. He then meets [[Smasher (comics)|Izzy Kane]], [[Cannonball]]'s wife, who tells him that Cannonball, who went missing in action during the takeover and was presumed dead, is still alive on another planet.<ref>''U.S.Avengers'' #10</ref>\n\nWhile travelling through space, Smasher and the U.S.Avengers are attacked by space pirates known as warpjackers. After a brief fight, the pirates tell them that Glenbrook is actually a planet named Kral X and that its ruler, Ritchie Redwood, is ruthless.<ref>''U.S.Avengers'' #11</ref> Arriving in Kral X, the heroes manage to help Cannonball and the planet's rebels in overthrowing Ritchie. After restoring order to the planet, the heroes head home.<ref>''U.S.Avengers'' #12</ref>\n\n===[[War of the Realms]]===\n\nAfter the Age of X-Man removes most X-Men members to an alternate reality, Sunspot reappears to assist [[Dani Moonstar|Mirage]] and the remaining X-Men repel Malekith's invasion of Midgard.<ref>Uncanny X-Men: War of the Realms #2 (2019)</ref> In a ploy to allow [[Magik (comics)|Magik]] to teleport the invading horde to Limbo, he breaks a cursed amulet blocking her powers, and in doing so, is vaporized, joining the fallen Valkyries in their journey to the afterlife.<ref>Uncanny X-Men: War of the Realms #3 (2019)</ref>\n\n==Powers and abilities==\n[[Image:XMEN SunspotPowerup.jpg|thumb|right|200px|Sunspot's energized state.<br/>''New Mutants'' #6<br/>Art by [[Diogenes Neves]].]]\nSunspot is a [[Mutant (Marvel Comics)|mutant]] whose cells have the ability to absorb [[solar energy]] and convert it for use as physical strength. He is also able to create thermal updrafts for flight, project heat and light, as well as concussive blasts of solar energy.<ref>{{Cite book|title=Marvel Encyclopedia: Updated and Expanded|last=|first=|publisher=|year=|isbn=|location=|pages=}}</ref> At will, he is able to take on a superhuman \"powered up\" form that is entirely nonreflective black, save for his eyes which turn a solid bright white. Though the color black optimizes solar absorption, he absorbs solar power at all times, not only when he is in his \"powered up\" form. If he has not absorbed sufficient amounts of solar energy in normal form, he will be too weak to \"power up\". Likewise, when not in direct sunlight, use of his superhuman strength rapidly exhausts the stores of energy within his body.<ref>{{cite journal|last=Buchanan|first=Bruce |title=The New Mutants: From Superhero Spin-Off to Sci-Fi/Fantasy|journal=[[Back Issue!]]|issue=29 |page=63|publisher=[[TwoMorrows Publishing]]|date=August 2008|location=Raleigh, North Carolina}}</ref>\n\nWhen in his solar form, Sunspot also has a [[corona]] effect, an aura that has been depicted in multiple ways, though two predominant conventions exist for its portrayal: one is that the air close to him manifests black globes of various sizes, reminiscent of [[Kirby dots]], and the other is a unified field glowing a bright yellow or white.  Although Sunspot can absorb energy from stars and reflected solar energy from the moon, the amounts that reach him on Earth are too minuscule to add significantly to his power. In other regions, such as [[Asgard (comics)|Asgard]], his power is significantly enhanced, allowing him - with much effort - to lift [[Volstagg]] off the ground for a few seconds before suffering a backache.<ref>''New Mutants Special Edition'' #1 (Dec. 1985)</ref>\n\nOriginally, Sunspot's superhuman power was limited solely to superhuman strength and enhanced durability, and then only in his solar form. Unlike many superhumanly strong heroes, Sunspot was unique in that his physical resistance to impact only increased somewhat when he employed his superhuman strength, and he was not bulletproof by any means. The phrase, \"Careful Bobby, you're strong, not invulnerable!\" or variations was seen many times. In addition, Sunspot's powers have radically changed and grown since the character was introduced; he can now withstand the force of a speeding eighteen-wheeler traveling at speeds of 100&nbsp;mph. Alongside surviving an A.I.M explosive charge latched onto his side.<ref>''Avengers World'' Vol. 1 #18</ref>\n\nSunspot maintained his original powerset for roughly the first ten years of his existence, remaining a super strong but vulnerable individual throughout the entire ''New Mutants'' series. During the mid-1990s in ''X-Force'' his powers began to change, under writer [[Fabian Nicieza]]. Nicieza had the supervillain Gideon capture Roberto and subject him to experimentation where the limits of Roberto's power absorption were tested by feeding him immense amounts of solar power. Roberto was rescued by X-Force, but the overload had permanently altered his powers in such a way that he was now able to release concussive blasts of solar energy, with a considerable heat and light projection component; this experimentation also made him immune to all types of heat and fire. He can also now absorb other forms of energy; such as heat, light or even radiation in a manner similar to photo/radio- or thermokinesis, It was believed they do not power up his abilities but this was proven false.<ref>''Hulk'' Vol 3 #3</ref><ref name=\"Avengers World Vol. 1 #19\">''Avengers World'' Vol. 1 #19</ref> Sunspot also has some capacity to manipulate light based energy effects, but it remains a largely unexplored portent of his mutant power.<ref name=\"Avengers World Vol. 1 #19\"/> It has been debated that Roberto would have reached these levels of his abilities of his own accord, and that Gideon's experimentation only increased his evolution process.\n\nThe fact that the solar blasts were concussive in origin led directly into ''X-Force'' #28, where Sunspot thinks of using them as a means of propulsion, and thus fly by blasting in the opposite direction of where he wanted to go \u2013 initially leaving a slight trail behind him, but in later years, Roberto would learn to use the propulsion more subtly \u2013 to appear to hover in place with no blast wake at all other than his usual \"powered up\" corona effect. His capacity to fly has similarly been enhanced as he is able to breach planetary orbit and reach Saturn's belt with relative ease.<ref>''Hulk'' Vol 3 #3-4</ref>\n\nSunspot also had the rituals and ideas of the [[Askani]] inside his head, due to a telepathic contact with Cable. While being strongly influenced by it for a while, the memories seem to have faded.\n\nSignificant non-superhuman abilities include business administration, as he owns and runs a multibillion-dollar international conglomerate. He is an Olympic-class athlete as the result of having been trained in combat by the X-Men and later by Cable. He is an expert in many languages (see below) and has an assortment of other more minor talents such as piloting aircraft. He was trained in swordsmanship by the Gladiators, and is also an excellent soccer player.\n\n==Other versions==\n\n===Age of Apocalypse===\nSunspot was in the X-Ternals with [[Jubilee (comics)|Jubilee]], [[Strong Guy]], and [[Gambit (comics)|Gambit]]. Like [[Robin Hood]], they take money from [[Apocalypse (comics)|Apocalypse]] and give to the poor. [[Magneto (Marvel Comics)|Magneto]] assigns them to travel to the [[Shi'ar]] Galaxy to steal the powerful [[M'Kraan Crystal]].<ref>''Gambit and the X-Ternals'' #1\u20134 (1995\u201396)</ref> Sunspot dies after absorbing too much energy in an attempt to help his teammates escape.{{issue|date=June 2017}}\n\n===Days of Future Now===\nIn this reality, Sunspot is shown as the leader of the [[Gene Nation]].{{Issue|date=March 2010}}\n\n===Mutant X===\nSunspot is part of a murderous team of '[[Marauders (comics)#Mutant X|Marauders]]', which consists of [[Jubilee (comics)|Jubilee]], [[Wolfsbane (comics)|Wolfsbane]], [[Cannonball (comics)|Cannonball]], and [[Husk (comics)|Husk]].{{Issue|date=May 2009}}\n\n===Ultimate Marvel===\nThe [[Ultimate Marvel]] version of Sunspot a.k.a. Roberto da Costa is an angry vigilante mutant of Brazilian descent. Originally came from Harlem in this continuity, he sees the [[Ultimate X-Men|X-Men]] as decadent [[Uncle Tom]] figures and has accused them of living in an ivory tower, considering themselves separate from \"second-class muties\" like himself. He also harbors a deep hatred for [[Magneto (Marvel Comics)|Magneto]] and his followers because of the anti-mutant hysteria that followed the Brooklyn Bridge's destruction at the [[Brotherhood of Evil Mutants]]'s hands.{{Issue|date=March 2010}}\n\nAfterward he has joined Emma Frost's [[New Mutants|Academy of Tomorrow]], a school for gifted beings. Initially, Roberto is confused as he knows his grades are not impressive. Emma assures him that grades (or even mutant powers) do not always classify a person as 'gifted'.{{Issue|date=March 2010}} Soon after Roberto is accepted into the school, he is in trouble: fellow student [[Polaris (Marvel Comics)|Lorna Dane]] is framed and imprisoned for the murder of several dozen people.  He is approached by Alex Summers (Polaris's boyfriend) and is convinced to help assist in breaking Lorna out. He works with [[Northstar (Marvel Comics)|Northstar]] and [[Cannonball (comics)|Cannonball]]. The team relies on Roberto's knowledge of New York City, but because Roberto had rarely been ''outside'' of Harlem, this reliance results in the team becoming lost. During this time, the X-Men attack them, and Roberto is subdued and removed from the fight.{{issue|date=March 2016}}\n\nMagneto has him killed in Ultimatum along with the rest of the Academy of Tomorrow except for [[Havok (comics)|Havok]].{{Issue|date=April 2009}} Sunspot is murdered in an attack.{{Issue|date=March 2010}} He is buried on the grounds of the [[X-Mansion]].<ref>''[[Ultimate Requiem]]''</ref>\n\n===What If?===\nIn \"What if Some of the X-Men Had Stayed In Asgard?\", Sunspot is one of the X-Men and New Mutants members who choose to remain in Asgard. When [[Hela (comics)|Hela]] attacks [[Storm (Marvel Comics)|Storm]] due to [[Loki (comics)|Loki]]'s intrigues, Sunspot rushes to aid Storm, to have his life taken away by the death goddess before he can land a blow on her.<ref>''What If?'' vol.2 #12</ref>\n\n==In other media==\n\n===Television===\n[[File:Sunspot-film.jpg|right|thumb|150px|[[Adan Canto]] as Sunspot in ''[[X-Men: Days of Future Past]]''.]]\n* Sunspot appears in ''[[X-Men: Evolution]]'', voiced by Michael Coleman. Depicted as seventeen-year-old boy, this version is a member of a junior team of X-Men. Born in Brazil, he moved to [[Xavier's School for Gifted Youngsters]], together with the other recruits, at Professor X's request. This version is something of a showoff, and sometimes gets into fights with his teammates, especially [[Berzerker (comics)|Berzerker]].\n\n===Film===\n* Sunspot was originally meant to appear in ''[[X-Men: First Class]]'', but was written out because of time and budget issues.<ref>{{cite web| url= http://www.bleedingcool.com/2011/05/24/matthew-vaughn-on-x-men-first-class-on-the-writing-credits-on-the-bond-influence-on-the-difficult-shoot-and-more/ | title= Matthew Vaughn On X-Men: First Class \u2013 On The Writing Credits, On The Bond Influence, On The Difficult Shoot And More| date= May 24, 2011 |first= Brendon |last= Connelly | website= BleedingCool.com| accessdate= March 12, 2016}}</ref>\n* Sunspot appears in ''[[X-Men: Days of Future Past]]'', portrayed by [[Adan Canto]].<ref>{{cite web|url= http://www.digitalspy.com/movies/news/a494134/x-men-days-of-future-past-adan-canto-confirms-sunspot-role.html |first= Hugh| last= Armitage| date= June 28, 2013| title= 'X-Men: Days of Future Past': Adan Canto confirms Sunspot role| website= DigitalSpy.com| accessdate= March 12, 2016}}</ref> This incarnation possesses a solar fiery aura, solar-powered flight and strength, and the ability to project solar energy and fire blasts. At film's beginning, Sunspot attempts to stall the advanced [[Sentinel (comics)|Sentinels]] so [[Kitty Pryde]] and [[Bishop (comics)|Bishop]] could change the past, but has his neck snapped by a Sentinel while in his solar form. During the battle, one Sentinel mimics Sunspot's powers in order to adapt to [[Iceman (Marvel Comics)|Iceman]]'s abilities, overcoming and killing him. Sunspot fought the Sentinels again so that [[Wolverine (character)|Wolverine]] could change the past. These events are erased later in the film's plot, after Wolverine's success in changing the events of decades-previous that lead to the Sentinels' creation.\n* Sunspot will appear in ''[[The New Mutants (film)|The New Mutants]]'', portrayed by [[Henry Zaga]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/heat-vision/fault-stars-writers-tackling-x-922893|title='Fault in Our Stars' Writers Tackling 'X-Men' Spinoff 'New Mutants' (Exclusive)|website=The Hollywood Reporter|language=en|access-date=2019-08-21}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://screenrant.com/deadpool-2-casting-x-force-sunspot-feral-shatterstar/|title=Deadpool 2 Is Bringing In More X-Force Characters|date=2017-05-09|website=ScreenRant|language=en-US|access-date=2019-08-21}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.tracking-board.com/stranger-things-star-charlie-heaton-to-play-cannonball-in-new-mutants/|title=\"STRANGER THINGS\" STAR CHARLIE HEATON TO PLAY CANNONBALL IN \"NEW MUTANTS\"|last=Sneider|first=Jeff|work=The Tracking Board|date=May 31, 2017|accessdate=May 31, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://collider.com/new-mutants-movie-cannonball-charlie-heaton/|title='New Mutants' Finds Its Cannonball with 'Stranger Things' Star Charlie Heaton|last=Goldberg|first=Matt|work=Collider|date=May 31, 2017|access-date=May 31, 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170601012439/http://collider.com/new-mutants-movie-cannonball-charlie-heaton/|archive-date=June 1, 2017|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist|2}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://marvel.com/universe/Sunspot Sunspot] at Marvel.com\n* [http://uncannyxmen.net/characters/sunspot Spotlight On Sunspot], UncannyXmen.net\n{{X-Men}}\n{{New Mutants}}\n{{X-Force}}\n{{Ultimate X-Men}}\n{{Avengers}}\n{{Portal bar|Speculative fiction|Brazil|1980s}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Sunspot (Comics)}}\n[[Category:American superheroes]]\n[[Category:Brazilian superheroes]]\n[[Category:Characters created by Bob McLeod]]\n[[Category:Characters created by Chris Claremont]]\n[[Category:Comics characters introduced in 1982]]\n[[Category:Fictional Brazilian people of American descent]]\n[[Category:Fictional Brazilian people of African descent]]\n[[Category:Fictional businesspeople]]\n[[Category:Fictional characters with fire or heat abilities]]\n[[Category:Male characters in comics]]\n[[Category:Marvel Comics characters with superhuman strength]]\n[[Category:Marvel Comics male superheroes]]\n[[Category:Marvel Comics mutants]]\n[[Category:S.H.I.E.L.D. agents]]\n[[Category:X-Men supporting characters]]\n", "name_user": "Netoholic", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200ePowers and abilities:post-move link fix", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Su